<HEADLINE> Britain to Start Constructive Talks on Lifting Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government has
indicated that it wants to work constructively to lift a year-old
European Union (EU) ban on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC television interview today, Agriculture
Minister Jack Cunningham said, "Our urgent objective is an end to
the beef ban and we need to map out in a much more constructive
way how we believe that can be achieved in partnership with our
European colleagues."
</P>
<P>
"There's no good threatening beef wars, as we saw the last
administration did. That made a difficult situation much worse, and
if we can do this within the terms of the Florence agreement --
then fine," Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cunningham made it clear that progress would not be
easy and Prime Minister Tony Blair's intention that his government
should be positive in its dealings with Europe would help.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to give the impression that I am a starry-eyed
optimist about it, but I think we will have a more constructive
dialogue and in doing so will improve the chances of getting more
of the kind of response we want to see," he said.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed the worldwide ban on British beef exports in
March 1996 after British scientists uncovered evidence that BSE or
mad cow disease could probably be transmitted to humans. Endiem

nnnn
23:52 23:52 g # NAB
</P>
</TEXT>
