<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Drug Sale Growth Slows Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The pace of growth for drug sales in
the world's biggest markets slowed down slightly in the first two
months of this year compared with 1996, according to a market
researcher.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by IMS International, the specialist
pharmaceuticals market researchers, showed that sales in January
and February in the world's top 10 drug markets were 26.4 billion
US dollars, 6 percent up on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate for the whole of 1996 was 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that the growth was led by the US, the largest national
market, where sales grew 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Japan and Germany ranked the second and the third biggest
markets, with sales growing 1 percent to 6.3 billion US dollars
and falling 1 percent to 2.6 billion US dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Sales by medical area showed sharp differences. Fastest growing
are sales of anti-infectives, which rose 13 percent to 3.2 billion
US dollars, making it the fourth biggest medical area.
</P>
<P>
Also growing quickly were sales of nervous system drugs, which
grew 10 percent to 3.6 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Digestive system drug sales grew far more slowly, which rose
only 4 percent to 4.2 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Heart drug sales were also hit by the expiry of patents,
growing only 4 percent to 5.2 billion US dollars, but they
remained the biggest selling medical area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
