<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Peace Process Gains Strong Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Participants in a seminar on the
Palestine issue, which ended here today, expressed support for the
middle east peace process and stressed the need for the full
implementation of the agreements reached between the Palestinians
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
A final document, issued at the conclusion of the United
Nations Asian seminar and NGO (non-governmental organization)
symposium on the question of Palestine, called on the two sides to
fulfill their agreements, especially the Declaration of Principles
in September 1993 and the Interim Agreement of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar, under the auspices of the Committee on
the Exercise of the Inalienable Rights of the Palestinian People,
was attended by about 200 representatives from Asia and other
regions, the United Nations, international organizations and NGOs.
</P>
<P>
The representatives and experts on the Middle East issue
emphasized the significance of the role that the countries of Asia
and Pacific had to play, and could continue to play, towards a
comprehensive, just and lasting settlement of the question of
Palestine in accordance with the relevant United Nations
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their support for the struggle of the
Palestinian people to achieve their inalienable rights, including
the establishment of their state, with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The participants also expressed serious concern over the
current stalemate in the peace process, particularly as a result
of the Israeli policies and practices.
</P>
<P>
The final document said that the Israeli settlements in the
occupied territory, including Jerusalem, are illegal. It called on
all countries to make additional efforts and take collective
measures to end that policy.
</P>
<P>
The document emphasized that NGOs constitute an emerging force
in the changing landscape of international politics.
</P>
<P>
It called on the Asia-Pacific NGOs to continue to work for the
achievement of a comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the
Middle East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
