<HEADLINE> British Foreign Secretary Promises New Era of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
said here today that London has entered a new era in its relations
with European continental countries and will fully participate in
the process of European construction.
</P>
<P>
He said that although his country will continue to protect its
own "vital interests" such as independently running its own border
control, Britain's interests will be better served if "we don't
fight with the rest of Europe on every subject, as the
Conservatives did."
</P>
<P>
Cook, who held talks today with French Foreign Minister Herve
de Charette, is on his first visit abroad since the establishment
of the new Labor government in Britain last week. He will go to
Germany later today to meet with his counterpart, Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
He chastised what he called the "sterile and negative" European
policy followed by the former Conservative government, and said
that Britain wishes to become "one of the three principal members
of the EU (European Union), working together to achieve the
realizations for the interests of our peoples."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the wish that the Intergovernmental
Conference on EU institutional reforms will be a success during
the EU summit to be held in mid-June in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed today to continue to work with France for adopting a
common position on the institutional reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cook also met with French Socialist Party First Secretary
Lionel Jospin and said that the Labor Party will develop relations
with its brother party in France and other European countries.
</P>
<P>
France, Britain and Germany will also issue a common
declaration today in Bonn on the banning of anti-personnel land
mines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
