<HEADLINE> Russia Approves Document on National Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
his Security Council today approved a document on the future of
the country's national security at a meeting in the Kremlin,
reported Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The document states in four parts the threats to the country's
security, the government objectives and strategy in the field of
national security, a Security Council official told Itar-Tass.
</P>
<P>
The 30-page document stressed that domestic social instability
and sluggish economy are the biggest threat to Russia's security
at present and in the foreseeable future, with military threat
excluded, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The priorities at present are to strengthen social stability,
complete and develop the idea of statehood and federalism, as well
as to boost the economy, said the official.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin admitted at the meeting that the planned
eastward expansion of NATO is one of the most serious problems
facing Russia.
</P>
<P>
Russia would take action against any threat to its security
from the expansion, which will include some eastern European
countries of the former Warsaw Pact bloc, Yeltsin warned.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was attended by Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin, First Deputy Prime Ministers Anatoly Chubais and
Boris Nemtsov and other senior officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
