<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Productivity Rises at Fastest Rate in 3 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The non-farm productivity in the
U.S. increased at an annual rate of 2 percent in the first three
months of this year, the fastest rate in more than three years,
the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. productivity increase in the quarter was nearly double
the 1.1 percent rate of the last quarter of 1996 and it was the
best since the 2.8 percent rate of the fourth quarter of 1993.
</P>
<P>
Productivity, the key measure of how fast living can rise,
measures output per hour of work. The sluggish growth since the
1970s in the U.S. is viewed as the root of many economic problems,
including relatively slow inflation-adjusted income growth.
</P>
<P>
It has averaged about a 1 percent gain a year for more than two
decades in the United States. But U.S. productivity increases
exceeded 3 percent a year in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
The report said that unit-labor costs -- a key ingredient in
pressures on product costs -- rose at a 2.7 percent annual rate in
the first quarter. That was up from 2.5 percent in the fourth
quarter but below the 3.3 percent rate in the second and third
quarters of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Worker compensation, when adjusted for inflation, rose at a 2.3
percent annual rate, the highest in five years and three times the
0.7-percent gain in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
The faster productivity can result in faster wages increases
without raising prices because workers are producing more with the
same amount of work.
</P>
<P>
Many U.S. economists believe that actual U.S. productivity
growth in recent years has been better than reported by the
government. That's because of the difficulty of measuring
efficiency gains in services.
</P>
<P>
They said that this would explain why economic growth has been
robust in the country, with unemployment near a 24-year low, while
inflation has been restrained at levels last seen in the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
