<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Confirms Rooivalk Helicopter Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad today confirmed for the first time that
his country will buy South African-made Rooivalk attack
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Cape Town after having been awarded
South Africa's highest honour, the Order of Good Hope, by
President Nelson Mandela, Mahathir said the Malaysian airforce
had evaluated the Rooivalk and "the chances are that we will
decide to purchase".
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, heading a large Malaysian business and Foreign
Ministry delegation, arrived in the country earlier in the day
from Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African Defence Minister Joe Modise indicated
that he will visit Malaysia in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Malaysia is negotiating with South
Africa's leading arms manufacturer Denel to buy eight Rooivalks,
and the first two helicopters are expected to be delivered soon.
</P>
<P>
During Mandela's state visit to Malaysia in March this year,
senior South African officials indicated that Mahathir had agreed
to go ahead with the Rooivalk deal.
</P>
<P>
However, officials from Denel, who has offices in the
Malaysia's capital Kuala Lumpur, declined to confirmed the deal,
saying it is Mahathir's prerogative to make an announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
