<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Monetary Authority to Issue 1997 Gold Coin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) announced here today that it will issue the 1997
Commemorative Gold Coin to mark the establishment of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The gold coin bears the standard Bauhinia design on the obverse
side, with a special commemorative design of the Hong Kong
skyline on the reverse side.
</P>
<P>
According to a HKMA spokesman, the gold coin is legal tender
with 1,000-HK-dollar face value. Produced by the Royal Canadian
Mint in 22 carat gold, each coin is individually numbered with a
Certificate of Authenticity.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that only 69,000 pieces will be available in
Hong Kong and the worldwide issue limit is 97,000, adding that
each Hong Kong Identity Card holder can apply for one gold coin
only.
</P>
<P>
The gold coin will be sold in Hong Kong for 3,988 HK dollars
(514.58 US dollars) each via public application through the
HongkongBank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
