<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislature Studies New Deputy Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
reviewed proposals for the number of deputies from ethnic
minorities to the next National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Participants at today's discussions of the 25th meeting of the
NPC Standing Committee said they believe that the proposal on the
number of deputies to be chosen from ethnic groups represents
equality among various ethnic groups in China, and conforms to the
realities of different locations.
</P>
<P>
In southwest China's Guizhou Province, people from various
ethnic groups account for 36.7 percent of the province's total
population and the number of deputies is 40 percent of the
province's total deputies, NPC Standing committee member Wang
Chaoyi said, noting that, "The proposal is reasonable and gives
priority to the minority ethnic groups."
</P>
<P>
To accord with the stipulation that deputies from ethnic groups
be about 12 percent of all the country's deputies, 360 deputies
should be elected from China's 55 ethnic groups. Each of the 35
ethnic groups that has a small population will have a deputy, to
ensure that every minority ethnic group has at least one deputy.
</P>
<P>
NPC Standing Committee member Lin Liyun said that although the
total number of deputies to the next National People's Congress
is smaller than to the current National People's Congress, deputies
from Taiwan Province will remain the same. "This shows that the
central government places great importance on compariots from
Taiwan Province," Lin said.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, many people of the Gaoshan
nationality in Taiwan who have visited the motherland have been
deeply impressed by the equality of people from various ethnic
groups, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the discussions also said they agree to the
proposal on the number of deputies at the provincial level. Yu
Xinglong, vice-chairman of the NPC Nationalities Committee, said
that the proposal is legal and reasonable. The number of deputies
is smaller but the quality is higher, Yu said, and this helps
improve efficiency and they will represent the wishes of the
people who elect them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
