<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Right-Left Support Rates Gap Continues to Narrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The gap of support rates between
France's ruling majority and the leftwing oppositions is
continuing to narrow, with 43 percent of the people wishing a
center-right victory in the legislative elections, and 41 percent
supporting the left.
</P>
<P>
A poll by the IFOP polling institute published today showed the
result three weeks from the holding of the first round of the
election on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen percent of the people polled refuse to give their
opinions, 12 points less than the previous poll conducted on April
24, while the support rate for the center-right increased by four
points, and that for the left by eight points since the last poll.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 40 percent of the people polled said that they have
a good impression of Socialist Party chief Lionel Jospin, and 33
percent said that they prefer Prime Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted on May 3 on 1,000 voters according to
the method of quotas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
