<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Hong Kong Stock Index Keeps Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua Correspondent Li Huailin) -- The Hang
Seng Index (HSI), a key indicator for blue chips on the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange, rose 26 points to close at 13,605 today.
</P>
<P>
The HSI has risen by 1,004 points in the past six trading days
after it stayed at around 12,500 points for 35 trading days in
nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
The six consecutive trading days started from last Wednesday
when the HSI soared by 303 points and on Monday this week, it
jumped 317 points.
</P>
<P>
In the middle of December 1996, the HSI topped 13,000 points
for the first time and on January 20, it reached 13,868 points,
the highest for the year.
</P>
<P>
However, on March 12, it began to fall from the 13,000 level
due to the decline of the sub-index of properties, according to
local stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said it is only natural that the HSI experienced
some adjustment after it had remained on the 13,000 level for
about five months.
</P>
<P>
The analysts also contributed the decline of the index to the
Hong Kong government's measures to curb speculations on the local
property market and possible rises in U.S. interest rates in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
But, they said, after the adjustment, an upward trend was
re-emerging on the local bourse, mainly pushed by the good
performance of China-funded stocks in Hong Kong, the sub-index of
properties and overseas stock markets.
</P>
<P>
Today's Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks the
performance of the 25 Chinese state enterprises listed on the Hong
Kong Stock Exchange, went up 32 points to 1,143, the highest
since it was launched by the HSI Services Limited in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The turnover in recent days was also on a high level, at 14.921
billion HK dollars (1.925 billion U.S. dollars) on Monday, 15.404
billion HK dollars (1.987 billion U.S. dollars) on Tuesday, and
14.763 billion HK dollars (1.904 billion U.S. dollars) today, much
higher than the average daily turnover of 9.102 million HK
dollars (1.174 million U.S. dollars) in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
