<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislators Review Administrative Control Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislators today
reviewed drafts of a law on supervision and a law on blood donations
at the 25th meeting of the Standing Committee of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The legislators agreed that the draft of the supervision law is
concrete and will play an important role in guaranteeing the
implementation of administrative policies and help build cleaner
government, and said that the law should be adopted.
</P>
<P>
They gave some advice on how to further improve the law,
pointing out that case study and court costs should be borne by
the state instead of by units being examined. Some suggested that
top state officials should also be subject to supervision at the
State Council level.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting also reviewed a draft of a blood donation law
and made suggestions for possible amendments.
</P>
<P>
Qin Zhongda, a member of the NPC Standing Committee, said that
in past discussions there were differences among committee members
about whether a voluntary or an obligatory blood donation system
should be adopted, and said that personally he prefers "the latter
to the former, and that the law should provide regulations to give
the donor some monetary assistance and time off for rest."
</P>
<P>
Other top legislators also shared their comments on this law,
discussing suitable penalties for illegal blood trade, examining
blood quality, and how to use the donated blood.  
</P>
</TEXT>
