<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICOM Appoints Agents for New Pager Service in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- China United Telecom Corporation
(UNICOM), the second largest state-owned carrier in China, marked
the inclusion of Hong Kong in its nationwide paging network today
by appointing Hutchison Telecom Corporation (HK) Limited and Asia
Paging Company Limited to launch the service in the territory.
</P>
<P>
Li Huifen, president of the UNICOM, told a news briefing here
this afternoon that "we take our service as a treasurable gift to
the people of Hong Kong" at a moment when Hong Kong is soon to
return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"It makes communications between China's inland areas and Hong
Kong easier, faster and closer," Li pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The UNICOM, initiated by the Ministries of Electronic Industry,
 of Electronic Power and of Railways, was officially set up with
the approval of the State Council in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
The UNICOM's paging network uses satellite technology to give
an extensive coverage, according to Hong Ming, general manager of
the corporation. He told reporters that only one access code --
191 for operator-assisted service and 192 for automatic paging
service -- is used throughout the network.
</P>
<P>
Apart from paging, the UNICOM is building a mobile telephone
network in China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the UNICOM has already started the
construction of its GSM network in 74 cities and finished such
construction in 33 cities, Li said, adding that the UNICOM's
paging network has, since September 1996, linked up 10 major
cities including Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen and Guangzhou, and
netted nearly 200,000 subscribes.
</P>
<P>
She told reporters that the paging network will extend to 100
cities with 700,000 customers by the end of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
