<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Program in Zimbabwe to Focus on Aids, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF) said today its major priorities for future programs in
Zimbabwe's health sector will emphasise on Aids and malaria, which
are killing hundreds of thousands of people in the country.
</P>
<P>
The malaria death toll of 949 since the beginning of the year is
the highest in many years due to above average rains in the country
while Aids continues to kill people at an estimated rate
of 500 a week.
</P>
<P>
In a report released at a meeting to review its program of
cooperation with the Zimbabwe government between 1995 and the year
2000, UNICEF said other major priorities would be to reach high risk
groups in farming areas and religious groups that resisted modern
medicine.
</P>
<P>
However, it cited major constraints as the declining government
health funding, high staff turnover, particularly at provincial
level, low staff morale and impact of Hiv/Aids and uncertainty
regarding implementation of health reforms.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that due to current social and economic changes
in the country, women and children were facing more difficulties than
before.
</P>
<P>
The review meeting is held to assist the government and UNICEF
to improve their policies and programs benefiting children.
enditem

