<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Court Rejects British Airways Request on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A French court today rejected a
request by British Airways for a suspension of authorization
allowing Air Algerie to use a terminal of the Roissy-Charles de
Gaulle airport in Paris, where the British air company's check-in
desk is located.
</P>
<P>
The Administrative Tribunal of Melun, southeast of Paris, said
that British Airways has failed to present evidence that it would
"irreversibly" suffer from serious consequences from a decision by
the Paris air traffic authority, the Aeroports de Paris, to place
Air Algerie in the same terminal.
</P>
<P>
Citing security concerns, British Airways has been refusing to
serve its customers at the same time when Air Algerie is serving
it since the Algerian air company resumed its flights from Algiers
to Paris on April 25, as the two companies share one baggage
conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
French authorities said they had taken enough security measures
to prevent terrorists from staging attacks, and that the check-in
desk of Air Algerie is closely watched by police.
</P>
<P>
The land used by the terminal in dispute belongs to the Commune
(township) of Mauregard, which is under the judicial
administration of Melun, a city southeast of Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
