<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Denies US Press Report on Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel strongly denied today a
Washington Post report that the United States is investigating
whether Israeli spies have obtained highly classified materials
from U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the U.S. secret service Federal
Bureau of Investigation was investigating whether Israeli agents
were spying on the U.S. through a senior U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
It said Israeli Ambassador to Washington Eliyahu Ben-Elissar
once asked Israeli agents to approach the code-named
U.S. official to get a copy of the secret letter of assurance
attached to the Hebron agreement sent by former U.S. Secretary of
State Warren Christopher to Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report, Israeli Prime Minister's Office
denounced it as "absolutely baseless." David Bar-Illan, senior
adviser to Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, said some
U.S. agencies that are not friendly to Israel were trying to
make the Jewish state "look bad."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy said Israeli diplomats around the
world had been given clear instructions and were never involved
in such activities. He expressed the hope that this dispute
would be over soon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Ben-Elissar categorically
denied the report as "false and baseless." "The whole story is
baseless, absolutely untrue," he said, adding it might be
released by some evil-intentioned people who tried to besmirch
and discredit Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Israel is not involved in any covered intelligence
operations dealing with the U.S. classified materials, because
this would be against all rules of Israel's successive
governments," he said.
</P>
<P>
The report was published just ahead of the visit by
U.S. Mideast special peace envoy Dennis Ross, who is to arrive
here later today on another mediation mission to break the
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli analysts believed that the report was a move taken by
the U.S. to show its impartiality in its mediation, because
Arafat and other PNA officials have been accusing the U.S. of
leaning toward Israel.
</P>
<P>
This is not the only spy scandal between Israel and the
U.S. despite of their close alliance. Former Israeli spy Jonathan
Pollard is now serving life sentence in a U.S. prison, and the
U.S. government has so far refused to release him despite
Israel's repeated appeals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
