<HEADLINE> Israel, Colombia to Cooperate in War Against Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Colombian President
Ernesto Samper Pizano said here today that in the coming weeks,
his country and Israel will start cooperation in the war against
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference following his meeting with
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, the president said that
Colombia and Israel will also set up joint technology research
centers.
</P>
<P>
However, the Colombian president refused to answer a question
on whether there were Israelis involved in the drug business in
his country.
</P>
<P>
Samper Pizano, who also serves as chairman of the Non-Aligned
Nations, arrived in Israel Monday and held a series of meetings
Tuesday with Israeli President Ezer Weizman and Foreign Minister
David Levy.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian president's visit to Israel is reportedly
arousing displeasure in the United States, which suspected him
of being linked to drug trafficking, and has forbidden his
entry.
</P>
<P>
Samper Pizano is suspected by the Clinton Administration of
having ties with drug barons, and Colombia's attorney-general
has accused him of financing his election campaign with funds
from drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
While the U.S. has not made any official statement to Israel
concerning the Colombian president's visit, Israel Radio reported
that last week a representative of the U.S. Embassy presented the
Israeli Foreign Ministry with a list of crimes Samper Pizano is
suspected of.
</P>
<P>
Every year since 1986, Colombia has been cited by the U.S.
State Department as a country involved in drug producing and
trafficking. 
</P>
