<HEADLINE> Foreign Minister: Germany Opposes Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
reiterated here today his country's objection to the Israeli
settlement policy that has disrupted the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are definitely against the settlement policies and we
support the Arab stand," Kinkel told a press conference after his
meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak this morning in the
archeological city of Luxor, about 520 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kinkel, who arrived here Tuesday, said Germany
tried to take a balanced approach to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"We have good relations with Israel, but on the other hand we
have good and balanced relations with all Arab countries," he
said, adding that Germany is committed to support Israel when
security is concerned.
</P>
<P>
He also affirmed the necessity of a European participation in
jolting the ailing Mideast peace process from several weeks of
crisis following Israeli construction of a new Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Kinkel-Mubarak meeting also covered the Euro-Egyptian
partnership, bilateral ties, inter-Mediterranean relations and the
visit due to be paid by Mubarak to Germany later this month,
said Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa who also attended the
two-hour talks.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries generally favor a European participation in the
Mideast peace process to balance the role of the U.S., a key
mediator in the region. 
</P>
