<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, Britain, France to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Germany, Britain and France issued a
joint statement today to seek intensified cooperation in arms
control and disarmament, in particular in efforts towards an early
international ban on the use and production of anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement, released in Bonn, London and Paris, said
that the foreign ministers of the three countries agreed to "give
particular priority to the early conclusion of an effective,
legally-binding international agreement to ban the worldwide use,
stockpiling, production and transfer of anti-personnel landmines."
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern over the continuing human sufferings from
minefields laid down in the past, they pledged to prevent the
creation of more minefields and to work together in international
fora to achieve this goal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
