<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IUCN to Stay Off Debate on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Conservation Union (IUCN) will
not intervene in the lobby by some African governments for lifting of
a ban in international trade in elephant products.
</P>
<P>
IUCN President Yolanda Kakabadse, who arrived in Zimbabwe
yesterday for a four-day visit, said here today that the union
would not take sides on issues involving
the down-listing of the elephant for fear of losing credibility as an
organisation whose members had different interests.
</P>
<P>
She said the IUCN, which has both governments and private sector
representatives as members, would only be able to supply concerned
African governments with technical information to enable them to make
decisions that would have interests of their people at heart.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''African elephant range states are the ones that will
have to face this situation, so we would only provide them with
technical information regarding the whole issue to enable them to
make wise decisions.''
</P>
<P>
''They will have to make sure that they take decisions on the
elephant issue after taking into consideration the available
technical information provided to them, but IUCN will not take any
pivotal role in this, even at the June cites meeting in Zimbabwe,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe in June will host a meeting of parties to the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (COTES) with most southern
African countries expected to use the platform to lobby for the
down-listing of the elephant from appendix one to appendix two, which
allows controlled international trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
