<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: SAARC's Top Priority: Poverty Eradication, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MALE, Maldives, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Poverty eradication and
economic cooperation are the top priority of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC), says Naeem Hasan,
the grouping's secretary general.
</P>
<P>
"There are two or three areas of major concern to SAARC in our
cooperation, one is the poverty eradication," Hasan told Xinhua in
an exclusive interview at the Bandos Island Resort near Male,
prior to the SAARC summit scheduled for May 12-14 in the Maldivian
capital.
</P>
<P>
There are almost 400 million people living below the poverty
line in the SAARC member countries which have a combined
population of one billion, Hasan said. "So we are making efforts
by each government, regionally and collectively to remove poverty
from our region."
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985 to promote regional cooperation
in economic, social, cultural and technological fields, groups
India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan and the
Maldives.
</P>
<P>
"As the earlier (SAARC) summits had decided, we should do so by
the year 2002. We have five years left to meet this target, so we
are going to looking into the progress that has been made in this
very important area of our cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
At their last summit in New Delhi two years ago, the SAARC
leaders established a mechanism in the field of poverty
eradication, and two rounds of meetings had been held since then
and a number of recommendations and concrete ideas on exchanging
information in this field had been made, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the coming summit, decisions will be made on these
recommendations. "As part of our poverty eradication program, we
will also emphasize issues relating to women and children, because
we would like women to contribute equally to the development of
South Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Due to many reasons, historical and cultural, the place of the
women is not what it should have been. That is why in our agenda,
the issues of women and children, education, health, medicine and
sanitation are very much emphasized," he said.
</P>
<P>
These issues, including the problem of malnutrition and the
high level of child mortality in South Asian countries, are going
to be discussed at the Male summit.
</P>
<P>
When asked if there are other obstacles standing in the way of
economic development in the region, Hasan insisted that the major
problem is poverty and the lack of resources. "The sheer size of
population in SAARC and the kind of conditions they live in is the
major challenge."
</P>
<P>
Besides poverty eradication and social issues, another major
area for regional cooperation in the last two years has been
economic and trade cooperation, Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
In December 1995, SAARC put into effect SAPTA, the South Asian
Preferential Trading Arrangement, pledging to create a free trade
zone -- the South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA) -- by the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is ultimately to realize SAFTA hopefully by the
year 2000, but not later than 2005. Naturally, this summit will be
given a full report on what we have been doing in the economic and
trade fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of trade negotiations have been completed under
SAPTA and the member countries are now exchanging tariff
concessions on over 2,000 products. "Now we are preparing for the
third round of trade negotiations and we hope the summit will give
its approval to the talks," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have also set up another important group which is going to
look into what are the steps required to move from SAPTA to SAFTA.
All the economic issues are being submitted to the summit through
the Committee on Economic Cooperation, which meets annually,"
Hasan said.
</P>
<P>
As a related effort, SAARC commerce ministers have met since
the New Delhi summit and the first SAARC trade fair was also held
in the Indian capital. The second commerce ministers' meeting and
the second trade fair will be held later this year in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In addition to cooperation at the official level among the
SAARC countries, the private sector has also been involved, Hasan
said. "The idea is that in our economic cooperation, it is a
double effort. There will be government cooperation side by side
with the private sector cooperation, because in almost all
countries of SAARC, the trend is towards liberalization, the
market economy and deregulation."
</P>
<P>
There will be a comprehensive report before the summit on
economic and trade issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
SAARC also has close cooperation with other international and
regional organizations, including United Nations agencies and the
European Union, and a number of cooperation agreements have been
signed with them, Hasan said. This trend has been increased in the
last two years, he said, adding that the SAARC countries are also
coordinating their positions on major global economic and social
issues.
</P>
<P>
"We have a very broad program of cooperation as we have 11
technical committees which deal with cooperation in the areas of
agriculture, science and technology, rural development, women
development and tourism," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked what achievements could be made at the Male summit,
Hasan said, "Well, let the summit comment." But he quickly added
that all previous SAARC summits had come up with important
declarations and that he was confident the coming summit will
chart a new direction for regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The trend in SAARC now is for a more action-oriented program.
In the first 10 years of SAARC's existence, we were talking in
general terms and now we are going into specific areas, specific
activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that intra-SAARC trade has been small -- about
three percent of their trade with the rest of the world. He
expected the percentage to grow to about 15 in three or four
years' time when the number of items for tariff concessions is
greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his views on recent signs of improved relations
between India and Pakistan, Hasan said they were a welcome
development.
</P>
<P>
"As secretary general, I do not follow the political and
bilateral developments between the member countries. But I can
certainly make a general comment that all these are very welcome
developments because the more there is peace, the more there is
stability in the region and the better bilateral relations.
Obviously it is going to have a very encouraging and soothing
effect on the development of SAARC," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These are encouraging signs that will certainly help SAARC
also to develop faster and have increased peace and economic
cooperation and other cooperation," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
