<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Calls Spanish King's Visit Landmark Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
hailed the just-concluded state visit to Russia by King Juan
Carlos I of Spain as an important step in the development of
Russian-Spanish relations.
</P>
<P>
Russian presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told
reporters today that during the visit the two heads of state
exchanged views on key aspects of bilateral relations and topical
international issues.
</P>
<P>
The two men agreed that the treaty of friendship and
cooperation signed in 1994 allowed their nations to reach a high
level of political dialogue and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin and Juan Carlos I noted that trade and
economic relations between the two countries have a considerable
untapped potential.
</P>
<P>
The trade turnover between Russia and Spain, which has
progressed successfully in recent years, amounted to nearly 1,870
million US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Russia mainly exported to Spain oil, petroleum products,
ferrous and nonferrous metal while importing from Spain meats,
vegetables, fruits and edible oil.
</P>
<P>
One of the main aims of the Spanish king's visit was to promote
investment and economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have decided to sign an agreement on mutual
protection of investments, avoidance of double taxation and
cooperation in the judicial and legal sphere, during the official
visit of Russian Premier Viktor Chernomyrdin to Spain, due to take
place later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
