<HEADLINE> UAE to Pump 2 Billion Dollars in Petrochemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 7 (Xinhua) - The United Arab Emirates (UAE) is
planning to pump some 2 billion U.S. dollars into its
pretrochemical sector as part of the efforts to diversify its
oil-dominated economy.
</P>
<P>
Related projects will be commissioned before 1999 and based in
Abu Dhabi Emirate, one of the seven sheikdoms of the UAE,
according to a study report by the state-owned General Industry
Corp (GIC) published today on the Arabic-language daily Al-Khaleej.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a 15-year industrialisation drive involving
the total investment of around 2.4 billion dollars in chemicals
and other non-oil sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Abu Dhabi will spend about 8.7 billion dirhams (some 2.4
billion dollars) on 40 industrial projects expected to go on
stream by year 2009 and new petrochemical plants expected to be
completed by 1999 will account for some three quarters of the
total," said the GIC study.
</P>
<P>
Two of the related projects were approved earlier this year by
the state's Supreme Petroleum Council (SPC). They will turn the
Gulf country into one of the top chemical producers in the Middle
East region.
</P>
<P>
One plant will produce 540,000 tons of ethylene di-chloride
and 420,000 tons of caustic soda per year. The complex in the
industrial area of Ruwais in Abu Dhabi will be owned by the Abu
Dhabi National Oil Company (ADNOC).
</P>
<P>
The other project, jointly owned by ADNOC and Borealis, a
Finnish-Norwegian venture, will have an annual output capacity of
450,000 tonnes of polyethylene and 600,000 tonnes of
ethylene. The Abu Dhabi-based ethylene complex will be expanded
later to 750,000 tonnes per year.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is among the top seven oil producers in the world and
its proven crude oil reserves constitute about 10 percent of the
total global oil wealth which stands at nearly one trillion
barrels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
