<HEADLINE> UN Official Urges Iraq to Implement Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations could never be
convinced before Iraq clears obstacles in implementing the UN
decision on dismantling weapons of mass destruction, a senior UN
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The UN Special Commission on Dismantling Weapons of Mass
Destruction of Iraq (UNSCOM) is facing difficulties in supervising
and implementing the decision made by the UN security council
after the 1991 Gulf war, Charles Duelfer, vice chairman of the
UNSCOM told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We (the UNSCOM) could never tell the UN security council
that Iraq is carrying out the council's decision on (destroying)
weapons of mass destruction unless these problems are settled,"
the UN official said before his departure for Bahrain after a
two-day visit to the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made after the 1991 Gulf War along with
an UN economic sanction against Iraq and it provides that Iraq
must destroy all of the weapons of mass destruction and biological
and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
However, during the implementation of the decision, information
provided by Iraqi officials on biological weapons are not
"enough" and always "uncorrect" and in addition, the UN has
been informed that Iraqis are hidding tonnes of chemical materials
which are banned by the UN decision, the UN official said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that investigations on the number of missiles
in the Iraqis' hands could not be finished until now.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has refused the UN investigation officials to
enter places suspected of storing weapons of mass destruction
claiming that the entry would violate the sovereignty of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Duelfer said that despite the difficulties, the UNSCOM will
continue its work of the supervision and implementation of the
decision. He also said that the recent change of the UNSCOM
chairmanship will not influence the work.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, the Australian ambassador to the UN
was appointed on May 1 the new UNSCOM chairman to replaced
Rolf Ekeus.
</P>
<P>
"The change will not affect the continuation of our work
because the work is based on analyzing information and facts,
it was not a political work which will change with the
change of the chairmanship," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UN official arrived here on Tuesday to brief the UAE
officials the latest developments of the implementation of the
UN decision. He denied that his tour is aimed at seeking
fund for the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UNSCOM is receiving money from the
oil-for-food deal which was signed by the UN and Iraq in May,
1996 and came into effect at the end of last year. The agreement
provides that Iraq was allowed to sell 2 billion dollars of oil
every six months. Most of the income will be used for purchasing
food and medicines to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people
while the rest will be used to pay the UN and Kuwait which was
occupied by Iraq during the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
Before the deal reached, some of the Gulf countries
subsidized the UNSCOM for the implementation of the UN decision
on dismantling weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM need to spend some one million dollars every
month, the UN officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Admits Paying Pensions to Ex-SS War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bonn government today admitted that
Germany has been paying pensions to ex-SS war criminals and
stressed that about 60 billion U.S. dollars had been paid in
compensation for Nazi war crimes.
</P>
<P>
According to Friedrich Bohl, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of
staff, German law allows pensions to be paid to Waffen SS members
who had been injured in combat, however excluding SS-Death's Head
members, who could only receive pensions as "war-damaged
civilians."
</P>
<P>
"Some regulations regarding rights of German war victims are
very difficult to understand for survivors of the Holocaust," he
said, adding that the relevant law was set in early years of West
Germany and based on the view then accepted by all democratic
parties, that social security and criminal affairs issues should
be kept apart.
</P>
<P>
Bohl said this in a statement in response to criticism by the
American Jewish Committee (AJC), which is running an advertisement
in the New York Times, that Germany refuses to compensate between
15,000 and 20,000 Nazi victims in Eastern Europe while paying
pensions to SS members.
</P>
<P>
SS-Death's Head units were concentration guards and the nucleus
of the crack SS-Death's Head Tank Division. The postwar Nuremberg
Trials declared the SS guilty of organizing and carrying out the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
Bohl stressed in the statement that the 240,000-head Waffen SS
consisted of not only volunteers but also large numbers of
conscripted Germans and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kohl's government and parliament would now be
searching ways to bar war criminals from receiving pensions.
</P>
<P>
Regarding AJC calls for more direct compensation to East
European Nazi victims, the statement noted that under a 1996
accord with the Jewish Claims Conference, no further financial
demands were to be lodged with the German government until 1999.
</P>
<P>
Bohl stressed that since the founding of West Germany in 1949,
Bonn has spent almost 100 billion marks (58 billion U.S. dollars)
in compensation for Nazi war crimes. In addition, an extra 3
billion marks has been made available to East European countries
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that much of the money will be spent in running
hospitals and nursing homes, not as direct compensation to Nazi
victims in Eastern Europe, which in many cases amount to a single
payment of 130 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that Bonn refuses to pay individual pensions
to Nazi victims in East European countries for fear of setting a
costly precedent that would add further burden to the government
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
