<HEADLINE> Bumper Harvest of Cotton Predicted for Swaziland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A bumper harvest of 46,000
tons of cotton is predicted this year for Swaziland's cotton
farming industry for the first time in seven years, the South
African Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
The good harvest will be the highest yield since 1990 when a
long-lasting drought, which only ended last season, first gripped
the small land-locked mountain kingdom, said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to Chief Executive of Swaziland Cotton Board Tom
Jele, the cotton farming industry only produced 14,000 tons of
cotton last year as it started to recover from the drought.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland is the second largest cotton producer in the
Southern African Customs Union (SACU) after South Africa. The
total cotton crop of the SACU countries, also include Lesotho and
Botswana, is expected to be 190,000 bales of lint.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers who abandoned growing the crop during the
drought are reportedly returning to cotton cultivation throughout
the kingdom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
