<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Secretary-General Praises China's Role in UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, on the second day of his first official visit to
China, held a press conference here today, highly praising China's
rapid development and its major role in the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Today, China is playing a major role in the United Nations and
has a major voice in the world. Its leadership and presence are
felt within the organization," Annan told those present at the
press conference, and that he is happy to be able to make this
trip to China so early in his term of office.
</P>
<P>
"I have had very useful talks with Chinese leaders already," he
said. Annan held talks with Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen and met with President Jiang Zemin earlier today.
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to continuing to have such talks with
Chinese leaders until the end of this visit," he said, explaining
that through these talks, he feels encouraged that China supports
the reform of the UN.
</P>
<P>
"With the full participation of all member countries, I'm sure
we will succeed in bringing effective and realistic reform to this
organization to which we are committed," he said.
</P>
<P>
His talks with the Chinese leaders involved a wide range of
issues, including UN reforms, disarmament, the return of Hong
Kong, and economic and social development. About the Hong Kong
issue, he said that time will prove that the concerns expressed by
people outside Hong Kong and China's inland areas have been
"misplaced."
</P>
<P>
He praised China's economic, cultural and technological
development as an example and something that is viewed with great
interest by the entire developing world.
</P>
<P>
"China has proved that it is possible for a developing country
to improve its situation in a relatively short period of time," he
said, and that, "The energy and enterprise of your people are
widely admired. I want to see something of this vast and
fascinating country."
</P>
<P>
In response to a question on human rights, he said that all
governments, whether in the north or the south, will have to
decide on their own how to organize society to achieve their human
rights objectives, and that, "This is the essential part of the
world today."
</P>
<P>
Annan will leave Beijing for Xi'an and Shanghai Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
