<HEADLINE> Australian PM Launches Toughest Attack on Hanson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard mounted his fiercest attack tonight on anti-Asian
immigration MP Pauline Hanson, accusing her of "empty populism,
cheap sloganeering and bitter and divisive recriminations."
</P>
<P>
Howard branded as "wrong" Pauline Hanson's attacks on Asian
immigration and Aboriginal funding and said the Hanson cure to
Australia's problems would be "worse than the disease".
</P>
<P>
He told a private sector group aiming to build links with Asia
in Sydney that Hanson is wrong when she says that Australia is in
danger of being swamped by Asians and claims that Australia is
headed for a civil war.
</P>
<P>
Australia's links with Asia would be vital to the nation's
political and economic future, the prime minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Howard's address came within days of polls showing the
government at a two-year low, with Hanson's fledgling One Nation
party picking up disaffected coalition voters.
</P>
<P>
The government attack on Hanson has been stepped up not because
of the polls but because she has started her own party, the prime
minister was quoted by the Australian Association Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hanson's political campaign sought to exploit
fear and instability without offering solutions or hope.
</P>
<P>
Other senior cabinet members, including Deputy Prime Minister
Tim Fischer and Foreign Minister Alexander Downer also publicly
condemned Hanson last week, accusing her of crippling the nation
in its attempts to engage in Asia.
</P>
<P>
In an address to Australian diplomats to some Asian countries,
Downer said the government would fight and destroy Hanson's ideas,
which were based on fear and ignorance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
