<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Opposes Setting Up North European Defense Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Sweden has reaffirmed its
opposition to setting up a defense alliance to provide security
for the three former Soviet republics in the Baltic region, which
are unlikely to get NATO membership in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Defense Minister Bjoern Von Sydow told reporters on
Tuesday that if the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
refuses to accept Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, three tiny former
Soviet republics in the Baltic region, Sweden has no reason to
shoulder bigger responsibility for security in the region.
</P>
<P>
His remarks showed that Sweden again refused to accept the idea
of establishing a North European Defense Alliance or the so-called
Baltic Security Zone as proposed by the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Sydow said that every country has its right to seek its own
security policy. Sweden will continue to pursue its policy of
non-alignment, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sweden is interested in cooperating with NATO, but it must
first take into consideration the result of negotiations between
NATO and the countries applying to join the alliance and the
result of negotiations between NATO and Russia, which has long
been opposed to NATO's eastward expansion, Sydow said.
</P>
<P>
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania applied for NATO membership after
the disintegration of the former Soviet Union. But their
applications were strongly opposed by Russia, which said it must
not let the alliance to expand to its border.
</P>
<P>
Given Russia's strong opposition, the United States and other
Western nations were not enthusiastic about the applications of
the three countries.
</P>
<P>
However, some U.S. and British politicians proposed that the
so-called Baltic Security Zone comprising Sweden, Finland,
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania be set up to prevent the three
countries from falling into the hand of Russia again.
</P>
<P>
But the proposal met with immediate opposition from Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Swedish Prime Minister Goeran Persson has said that Sweden
likes to cooperate with Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania in any field
except the military one.
</P>
<P>
Sweden has said that the European Union (EU) should accept the
three countries and then the EU, through NATO, can help them
in security affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
