<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM to Meet Albright in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Foreign Minister, Ioannis
Kasoulides will meet with his U.S. counterpart, Madeleine
Albright in Washington on June 6, to discuss the Cyprus
problem and bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency today, this was announced
by Kasoulides on his return from Athens Wednesday night, where
he had a meeting with Director for Southern European Affairs
at the U.S. State Department, Carey Cavanaugh.
</P>
<P>
Describing the timing of the meeting with Albright as
"important", Kasoulides said it coincides with the on-going
U.N.-led proximity talks between President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel is
conducting proximity talks through bi-weekly separate meetings
with Clerides and Denktash in a bid to prepare the ground
for face-to-face talks on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.N. Chief Kofi Annan will
invite the two communities' leaders to a direct negotiation by
the beginning of June.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said the U.S. official in the meeting expressed his
country's satisfaction with the Cyprus government decision to
suspend overflights of Greek military aircraft during a Greek
military exercise code-named "Toxotis", now under way.
</P>
<P>
Cavanaugh also welcomed steps taken by both sides in Cyprus
aimed to create the suitable climate for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official expressed his government's determination to
be actively involved in efforts toward a Cyprus settlement to
the benefit of stability and security in this part of the
Easter Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of an Athens-supported coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
