<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Official Supports China's Integration With World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Flemming Larsen, an official with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF), said in Shanghai today
that the belief of some developed countries that the economic
prosperity of China and other developing countries has been
achieved by large amount of exports and the loss of job
opportunities in developed countries is incorrect.
</P>
<P>
At an IMF meeting last week in Washington, a consensus was
reached that the real reason for the decline in the need for labor
in developed countries, especially European countries, is the
improved technology. Technological improvements, which make
industry more advanced and complex, have increased the demand for
skilled workers and in turn increased their salaries. Unskilled
workers, however, have fewer job opportunities and lower salaries,
Larsen pointed out.
</P>
<P>
This conclusion has been backed up by economic theory and
statistics, he said. Therefore, developed countries should not
make trade tariffs for developing countries and should let them
have their due market share.
</P>
<P>
China's economic reforms so far have been successful, and the
rapid development of China's economy is encouraging, but the
country is facing two major challenges from inflation and the
reform of state-owned enterprises. Whether or not China will be
able to resolve the two problems resolutely and effectively has a
bearing on its long-term prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, China should accelerate the process of integration
with the world economy, he said, and that this not only includes
trade, but also direct and indirect investment, and extensive
cooperation in technology, information and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Larsen is heading an IMF delegation that arrived in Shanghai on
May 5. It has held talks with economic and financial experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
