<HEADLINE> China Describes Desertification Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- China today made public the results
of its first survey on desertification, showing that 17.6 percent
of its total land area is deserts or desertified land.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, Vice-Minister of Forestry, said at a press
conference that, over the past twenty years, the desertification
process spread at a speed of 2,460 sq km per year, and that, based
on the definition of a UN convention, the area of desertified land
in China will be 2.62 million sq km, 27.3 percent of the country's
total land area.
</P>
<P>
According to the vice-minister, most land suffering from
desertification is located in the "three north" region, meaning
the north, northwest, and northeast China. "As much as 80 percent
of the land in this region is currently suffering from
desertification," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that combating desertification has become an urgent
task, since the estimated economic loss from it reaches 54 billion
yuan (some 6.7 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The country-wide survey on desertification, the first of its
kind in China, started in 1994, and involved nearly 10,000
technicians.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the results of the survey, which are
believed to be reliable, have officially been accepted by the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
As one of the most critical environmental problems on earth,
one that expands at a speed of five to seven sq km per year
worldwide, desertification is believed to affect a third of the
earth's land area and a fifth of its population. The total yearly
economic loss from desertification is estimated at 42 billion US
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
