<HEADLINE> Colombian President Urges Greater Egyptian Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Colombian President Ernesto
Samper today called upon Egypt to play a more active role in
restoring trust between Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"Trust is still missing between the two parties... I asked
President Hosni Mubarak to lend more help to the peace process,"
said Samper after a meeting with his Egyptian counterpart in the
the Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh, some 220 kilometers
southeast of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Samper, who is on a region tour, has held talks with Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat on the latest developments in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He was received by President Mubarak in spite of a U.S. charge
that the Colombian leader had taken billions of dollars from the
Cali cartel, which is notorious for its drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
"Despite existing differences, we understand the importance
of returning to the negotiating table and finding a solution to
this problem," he added.
</P>
<P>
Samper, current chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement(NAM), said
NAM's role in the Mideast peace process is to link member nations
and non-member nations to the process.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian president said that he believed talks would be
resumed with the help of the international community, the spirit
of UN resolutions and the desire of both parties to reactivate the
process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa told reporters that the
NAM could play a role in the Mideast by "supporting the peace
process and land-for-peace principle and rejecting the settlement
policy."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been disrupted since
Israel decided to build a new Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem on March 18.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross has started another round of
shuttle visits between Jerusalem and the Gaza Strip today, in an
effort to restart the stalled Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
