<HEADLINE> Japanese Fuji to Make Film in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Fuji Photo Film Co. will begin
manufacturing film in the U.S. for the first time, making the
competition between the Japanese company and its rival Eastman
Kodak Co. more tense.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported today that Fuji will spend 200
million U.S. dollars on a facility to make film in Greenwood,
S.C., and to boost its existing papermaking capacity there. This
will bring its total investment there to about 1 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Fuji's ability to produce both film and paper in the U.S. will
make the company more aggressive in pricing and accelerate its
ability to fill U.S. orders, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Fuji first began manufacturing in the U.S. nine years ago. At
that time, it was only making printing plates for the graphic arts
industry. But since then it has invested heavily to accommodate
the production of photographic paper, single-use cameras and
videotape, among other products.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Fuji has imported all film sold in the U.S. from the
Netherlands and Japan, paying 3.7 percent tariffs. While it will
now rid itself of shipping and import costs, the company will also
forgo and benefit from foreign-currency fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
Fuji's expansion comes as Fuji and Kodak fight a trade case
before the World Trade Organization, which is hearing Washington's
argument that barriers keep Kodak from the Japanese market. By
making film in the U.S., Fuji won't have to worry about tariffs or
possible repercussions in the U.S. from the WTO case, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
