<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Banks Urged to Learn from Better Credit Risk Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's banks should maintain
their competitive advantage by practicing better risk management,
said a senior financial expert from the international professional
services firm Arthur Andersen.
</P>
<P>
Andy Cheung, senior manager of Arthur Andersen, a business unit
of the global multi-disciplinary professional services provider
Andersen Worldwide, told a press conference this afternoon that
"banks in Hong Kong are nowhere near crisis, remaining very sound
and well-capitalized."
</P>
<P>
But "it would be prudent and in the banks' interests to learn
from overseas experience and international best practice in credit
risk management, to maintain their competitive advantage," Cheung
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to him, 26 of Hong Kong's largest locally
incorporated banks recorded charges for loan losses totaling 3.9
billion HK dollars (500 million U.S. dollars) in 1996, more than
double the total of 1.9 billion HK dollars (over 243 million
U.S. dollars) recorded in 1995 and nearly 3.5 times higher than
the 1.1 billion HK dollars (141 million U.S. dollars) recorded in
1994.
</P>
<P>
"This may sound alarming," Cheung said, noting that the Hong
Kong-based banks compare "very favorably" to banks in other
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
He cited his firm's study as showing that banks in Hong Kong
incurred loan losses which amounted to 7.2 percent of profit
before tax in 1996, while British banks incurred 20.5 percent and
the largest banks in the United States recorded 20.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Banks in Hong Kong have low bad debt charges compared to many
banks in other countries, Cheung went on to say. "However, this
does not necessarily indicate that our bankers are better or worse
at managing credit risk, as they have traditionally been favored
by a healthy and growing economy, high savings rates, lucrative
interest margins and a strong property market," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0065 </DOCNO>
