<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Demands Security for Local Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition today
urged the government to stop terrorism and anarchism prevailing in
some rural areas to ensure security for the upcoming local
elections.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the Nepali Congress (NC) party today met Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and presented him a memorandum,
demanding that stern actions be taken against those who had foiled
the nomination filing process for the local polls at many western
hilly villages.
</P>
<P>
Would-be candidates had failed to file their candidacy at over
40 villages in West Nepal due to death threats from a leftist
guerrilla movement in a boycott campaign, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
The candidates who filed their nominations earlier at other
villages were reportedly withdrawing from the elections, scheduled
for May 17, as the radical guerrillas strengthened their threats
by killing a candidate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NC delegation, led by party secretary Taranath Ranabhat,
also urged the government to protect the life and property of
those who want to contest in the elections and ordinary voters.
</P>
<P>
The NC party currently controls most of the country's over
4,000 local administration bodies at village, municipality and
district levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
