<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova, Trans-Dnestr Sign Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The leaders of Moldova and the
breakaway Trans-Dnestr region today signed a memorandum in the
Kremlin for the normalization of relations between them.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to develop relations "within the framework
of a common state, and within the borders of the former Soviet
republic of Moldova dating from January 1990," an Itar-Tass news
agency report said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed by Moldovan President Petru
Lucinschi, Trans-Dnestr leader Igor Smirnov and three guarantors
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin, Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma and Niels Helveg Petersen, acting chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Trans-Dnestr is a sliver of land in eastern Moldova dominated
by the Russian-speaking population. But two-thirds of the
Moldovian population are ethnic Romanians. The nation was part of
Romania before World War II.
</P>
<P>
The fear of Moldova's reunification with Romania drove
Trans-Dnestr separatists to unilaterally declare independence in
1992, triggering an eight-month civil war against Moldovan
government forces.
</P>
<P>
The war, which left about 700 dead, ended when the 14th Russian
army based in Trans-Dnestr intervened. So far, some 6,500 Russian
troops are still stationed in Trans-Dnestr.
</P>
<P>
At today's signing ceremony, Lucinschi said, "we will think
that we have turned over a fresh page in history and are beginning
a negotiation process on how to normalize the situation."
</P>
<P>
Smirnov called the signing of the document "historic," saying
that both he and the Moldovan leaders want to work "to create, not
to destroy."
</P>
<P>
Russia, Ukraine and the OSCE also hailed the agreement as a
"move to strengthen the atmosphere of mutual trust, stability and
security throughout the region." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Surrender in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A group of the Moro Islamic
Liberation Front (MILF) rebels surrendered today to the Philippine
Armed Forces Southern Command in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The group, including one commander and his 12 followers,
yielded some high-powered weapons, including two grenade
launchers, and other ammunition to the military, according to
Southern Command Information Officer Capt. Salih Indanan.
</P>
<P>
These rebels had been operating in Maluso town in Basilan
island.
</P>
<P>
Indanan said they will be processed and provided with
assistance under the National Unification and Development Program
(NUDP) of the government.
</P>
<P>
They will also receive cash for the guns they surrendered so as
to make a living while waiting for financial assistance for
livelihood projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Indanan, several groups of MILF rebels have
surrendered to the government forces during the past months due to
the government's peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the Muslim extremist Abu Sayyaf are the only two
Muslim rebel groups still fighting the Philippine government
forces.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), is currently the largest anti-government force in
the country, with an estimated membership of 12,000.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which refused to be included in the peace deal forged
last September between the MNLF and Manila, began its own peace
talks with the government this January. But Abu Sayyaf has shunned
peace talks with Manila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
