<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets UN Secretary-General (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has successfully put its inflation under control while
the economy grows and the standard of living of its 1.2 billion
people has been improving, Annan said, which is a great
achievement that has caught the world's attention.
</P>
<P>
UN departments have co-operated well with China and have
completed many projects successfully, he said, and that the
cumulative experience will help the UN increase co-operation with
other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that, in spite of its achievements in economic
construction, China, which is the world's biggest developing
country, still faces challenges and that more than 58 million
Chinese haven't solved the problem of adequate food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
However, China is full of confidence of its future, he said,
and expressed the conviction that as long as China sticks to its
reforms and opening up, it can keep the rate of growth high and
inflation low to the end of this century and into the next.
</P>
<P>
Co-operation between China and UN agencies has been sound,
Zhu said, and China's development has benefited from the
international co-operation and UN aid and that China hopes to
increase its co-operation with the UN in the future.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the world is colorful and diverse and that
countries differ not only in social systems, values, and ideology,
but also in historical traditions, religions, and cultural
backgrounds. If these differences are respected, he noted, all
countries will be able to co-exist peacefully, increase
communications, and expand co-operation.
</P>
<P>
It is important that all countries learn from each other, but
this can only be based on a principle of mutual respect, equality
and mutual benefits, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
