<HEADLINE> Nepali FM Leaves for SAARC Council of Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Foreign Minister Prakash
Chandra Lohani left here today for Male, capital of the Maldives,
for a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
The session of the Council of Ministers precedes a three-day
SAARC Summit from Monday.
</P>
<P>
Talking to official media at the airport, Lohani said that
various programs, including poverty alleviation launched under the
SAARC umbrella, will be assessed during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Discussions concerning free trade in the South Asian region
will also be held during the meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other topics, including control of drug trafficking, terrorism
and food security, will also be discussed, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the foreign minister, informal talks between
Nepali and Bhutanese leaders on the lingering Bhutanese refugee
problem are expected at the SAARC summit.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 Bhutanese refugees, mostly of Nepalese origin,
have been living in eight refugee camps in east Nepal after they
fled to Nepal via India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
