<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Boost Economy With New Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government has
decided to take action to speed up its slow economic growth and
boost the country's competence in the world market, official
sources here said.
</P>
<P>
The government will throw more support behind the back of those
manufacturers that start business mainly by application of new
technology, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The country will set up training centers and universities to
train qualified industrial personnel.
</P>
<P>
The government is obliged to work out a program by the end of
this month on establishing a system to build links of human
resources supply between universities and the industries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will also increase investment in technical
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Lawmakers Call for Marine Exploration Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Qin Zhongda and Yang Zhenhuai,
members of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee, said here today that China should formulate laws and
regulations on developing marine resources as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Chinese lawmakers noted that better use can be made of China's
marine resources by drafting laws and improving management.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive management system for co-ordinating rational
development and utilization of marine resources should be
established eventually to protect marine resources and China's
marine environment, they said at the on-going 25th plenary meeting
of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
China's marine output value has grown at a rate of 25 percent
annually since 1990, and was 287.7 billion yuan (34.6 billion US
dollars) last year, compared with 43.9 billion yuan in 1990, and
6.4 billion yuan in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that the increase will be higher than that
for the national economy. Offshore oil exploration, tourism, the
marine chemical industry, and other new marine industries are
emerging as pillar industries in addition to marine fisheries,
salt, and ocean transportation. In 1996, China's offshore oil
output was 18 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Some hi-tech marine industries are expected to grow up in next
century, such as desalination of seawater, direct utilization of
seawater, a marine pharmaceutical industry, marine mining, and
utilization of sea energy.
</P>
<P>
"China should list offshore exploration as part of its
development strategy from now on so that it can have some
achievements in this field in next century," Qin said, pointing to
the fact that in recent years, many coastal countries have placed
great importance on exploring marine resources and developing
marine industries.
</P>
<P>
The total output value of the world's marine industries will
surpass 1.5 trillion US dollars early in the 21st century,
compared with 670 billion dollars in 1992, and 13 billion dollars
in 1969. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
