<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Call For Greater Efforts to Wipe Out Poverty (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another member, Xiong Qingquan, said that the aged, the ailing,
and handicapped, and orphans in rural areas account for three to
five percent of the poverty stricken population, and should be
helped with a social security system.
</P>
<P>
Other measures for rooting out poverty in this century that the
legislators discussed included investing more in education and
technology, and improving Party and government leadership in this
work.
</P>
<P>
Dong Naifang and Yang Haibo said that food, clothing, and
shelter are essential for destitute people but are by no means the
ultimate goal of the poverty alleviation efforts. Dong noted,
"They should be better educated and understand useful practical
technology to make themselves better off with their own hands,"
and it is the government's duty to invest more in education and
practical technological development in these areas.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Wang Bingqian, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing
Committee, said, Party heads in poor areas should be held directly
responsible for solving this problem.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Guoxiang, a member of the NPC Standing Committee, said
moreover that officials in poor areas should establish direct
contacts with poor families "so that they can understand the
people's problems." He also proposed that Party organization
departments send officials up for promotion to poor areas, to see
whether they are capable.
</P>
<P>
Buhe, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, said that
the poverty eradication work must be understood as a key political
issue that is related to narrowing the gap between town and
country and consolidating unity among ethnic groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
