<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Economic Ministers Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The 32nd session of the
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and 23rd meeting of the
Conference of Ministers Responsible for Economic and Social
Development and Planning today adopted a declaration, noting that
poverty which constitutes the most serious problem facing Africa
"can be reduced and eventually eradicated by sustained high rates
of economic growth."
</P>
<P>
The declaration and five resolutions have been adopted at the
end of the 32nd session of the ECA and the 23rd meeting of the
Conference of Ministers Responsible for Economic and Social
Development and Planning.
</P>
<P>
''The declaration on accelerating trade and investment in
Africa'' said that a sustained high rate of investment and
production ''requires considerable resources which can be
obtained mainly from an increased rate of domestic savings,
supplemented by official development finance and foreign
investment''.
</P>
<P>
the meeting is concerned about the long-term declining trend
of official developmemt assistance in spite of economic
restructuring efforts and continuing need of development
resources.
</P>
<P>
the declaration welcomed the debt reduction initiative for the
highly indebted poor countries recently proposed by the World
Bank and the International Monetary Fund, saying that ''This is a
first step in the right direction''.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that in order to achieve the goals of boosting
domestic savings and investment, attracting substantial private
foreign capital transfers, and expanding trade with the rest of
the world, african countries must accomplish such prerequisities
as improving information flow on developments in Africa,
modernizing, expanding and diversifying production, strengthening
international competitiveness and striving for genuine regional
economic integration.
</P>
<P>
It urged Africa's bilateral partners to continue to provide
direct financial support and to extend indirect support through
tax incentive to their national investors participating in
infrastrucutre development projects in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It also urged multilateral development finance institutions,
notably the African Development Bank, the African Export-Import
Bank and the World Bank, to continue to play an important role in
providing technical assistance to African countries.
</P>
<P>
A resolution on reform of the intergovernmental machinery of
the ECA decided that the Conference of African Ministers
Responsible for Economic and Social Development and Planning will
meet on biennial basis and the next meeting will be in 1999. The
Conference of African Ministers of Finance will be convened
biennially in alternate years to the meeting of the Conference of
African Ministers Responsible for Economic and Social Development
and Planning.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also approved the creation of the African Women's
Committee on Peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Commercial Press Marks 100th Birthday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Commercial Press, one of China's
oldest publishing houses, celebrated its centenary today in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
State Councillor Li Tieying sent a letter of congratulation to
the centennial celebration, calling it a "great event" in China's
press history.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged the country's publishers to learn from the
splendid history of the publishing house, and make a greater
contribution to China's modernization.
</P>
<P>
Founded in Shanghai in 1897, Commercial Press is regarded as
the first modern publishing house in the country. It was moved to
Beijing in 1954, specializing in foreign works of philosophy and
sociology and dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
In the past four decades, it has published more than 10,000
kinds of books, and has maintained its prestige in the publishing
industry for its academic value and quality of printing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
