<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges U.N. to Approve Deals with Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordan intensified diplomatic
contacts with the United Nations Sanction Committee as the world
body repeatedly delayed to approve some of the contracts Jordan
signed with Iraq to supply the country with life necessities.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's permanent representative to the U.N. is discussing
with the concerned departments on the contracts that are still
undecided up to now, said Hani al Mulqi, Minister of Industry,
Trade and Supply, in an exclusive interview with local Arabic
newspaper Al-Rai, which published today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Jordanian minister was expected to get
a clarification from these departments no later than next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another senior government official, who declined to
be identified, said that the Jordan had to intensify contacts with
the U.N. for quick approval of the contracts, because the world
body's delay forced some of Jordan's contractors to stop
production or transaction and lose money day by day.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, all together 13 contracts from 13 Jordanian
companies have received permission from the Sanction Committee to
supply Iraq with detergents, cooking oil and medicine worth more
than 35 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 Jordanian firms who signed contracts with Iraq are
still awaiting to receive the U.N. consent.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food accord, Iraq is allowed by the U.N. to
sell oil worth of 2 billion dollars, 1.3 billion of which will
be used to buy food and other life necessities for the country's
19 million citizens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has maintained its seven-year embargo on Iraq since
the Gulf war ended and the Iraqi troops were driven out of its
oil-rich neighbor Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Before and during the Gulf war, Jordan sided with Iraq. Later
after the war, it distanced itself from Iraq in order to improve
its relations with the Gulf nations and the western states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
