<HEADLINE> Mandela to Apply for Amnesty, Says ANC Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 8 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela will apply for amnesty from the government-appointed
Truth and Reconciliation Commission, said Acting Secretary-General
of the ruling African National Congress (ANC) Cheryl Carolus.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will apply for collective responsibility with the
party's leadership instead of applying as an individual, Southern
African Broadcasting Associaition quoted Carolus as reporting
today.
</P>
<P>
Carolus said Mandela had already served 27 years in prison for
his active role in the struggle against apartheid which had been
condemned globally as a crime against humanity.
</P>
<P>
She said the ANC had decided that past and present members of
the party must apply for collective responsibility to cover acts,
omissions and offences resulting from the liberation struggle.
</P>
<P>
The Truth and Reconciliation Commission, chaired by retired
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, is hearing evidence from people
who committed crimes in the course of defending or fighting
apartheid.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tutu announced May 10 as the deadline for people
seeking amnesty for crimes committed. He said anyone failing to
come forward to confess by the ultimatum would be liable to
prosecution. 
</P>
