<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With UN Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, welcoming
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan this afternoon on his
first visit to China since taking office last December, said that
China's firm and unshakable state policy is not to practise
hegemonism nor seek external expansion.
</P>
<P>
China's stability and prosperity do not threaten any country,
but only serve as greater contributions to world peace and
development, the Chinese leader said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said he believes Annan's visit will give him a deeper
understanding of China.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he was honored by being able to visit China as the
UN Secretary-General because he has an opportunity to thank the
Chinese government and people for their support and contributions
to the UN.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the UN is the most important large
international organization, and for the past 50 years, it has made
important contributions to safeguarding peace and prosperity in
the world.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that, as mankind moves toward a new century,
the UN can sum up the positive and negative lessons of the past
50-some years and act in strict keeping with the goals and
principles of the UN Charter, care more about economic and social
development, and make greater contributions to a more beautiful
world in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that an increasing number of countries have noticed
the great role the UN has played, and that in a number of major
international issues, like environmental protection, disarmament,
and the fight against drug trafficking, no country could do it on
its own. Only with joint efforts of all countries under the UN
banner, can these challenges be met in an effective way.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told Annan that on April 25, China ratified the Chemical
Weapons Convention and became an original signatory country. He
added that China hopes all other countries, especially those with
chemical weapons, will approve the convention at an early date to
realize its goals of a complete prohibition and thorough
destruction of global chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he appreciates China's support for the convention,
and that relations between the UN and China have been good from
the very beginning and that bilateral cooperation has been
fruitful.
</P>
<P>
The fine cooperation between the UN missions in China and
Chinese departments have set a good model for the international
community, he said, and believes that this relationship will
continue to be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that, as permanent member of the UN Security
Council, China is fully aware of its duties for world peace and
security, and "will, as always, use its independent foreign policy
of peace and will strive to develop friendship and co-operation
with various countries."
</P>
<P>
China opposes hegemonism and power politics even when its
economy is developed in the future, Jiang said. Some people are
spreading the "China Threat" rumor in the international arena, he
noted, but this is "totally groundless".
</P>
<P>
Jiang welcomed Annan to the Hong Kong handover ceremony on the
midnight of June 30, and said that the exercise of sovereignty
over the territory is an important event in modern Chinese history
and a major international event.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong returns to the motherland, he explained, China
will adopt the policy of "One country, two systems", "Hong Kong
people governing Hong Kong", and a high degree of autonomy, and
that Hong Kong, as a bridge to the rest of the world, will
maintain its prosperity and stability on a long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
This is in the fundamental interest of China and is a
contribution to the world, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that he is glad that to have a chance to attend the
handover ceremony and that he has a firm belief that Hong Kong
will maintain its prosperity and stability in the future.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Ambassador Qin Huasun, Chinese
Permanent Representative to the UN; Tang Jiaxuan, Vice-Foreign
Minister of China; and UN Undersecretary-General Jin Yongjian.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived here Wednesday as guest of the Chinese
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Informal Contact Continues for Pak-India Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MALE, the Maldives, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Informal contact is going
on to prepare for a meeting between the prime ministers of
Pakistan and India, which has been scheduled for May 12 on the
fringes of a summit of South Asian leaders here, a senior
Pakistani official said today.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad Ahmed, Pakistan's foreign secretary, told Xinhua that
he already had some kind of informal contact with his Indian
counterpart Salman Haidar, but they have yet to hold informal
discussions.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed is here attending the foreign secretaries' meeting of the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) which is
preparing the agenda and programs for the grouping's summit to be
held here on May 12-14.
</P>
<P>
"We are meeting with each other here during the course of these
meetings ... We are in informal contact to prepare for that (the
prime ministers') meeting," Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
"We will certainly have informal discussions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked about what is to be discussed at the Pakistani-Indian
summit, Ahmed said, "Our agenda is how we can address ourselves to
the whole range of outstanding issues between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"The Kashmir issue is on the top agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said the Pakistani-Indian summit might be held in the
afternoon on May 12 instead of in the morning ahead of the opening
of the SAARC summit as had been scheduled. "There might be a
little readjustment because we are going to have an inauguration
(of the SAARC summit) in the morning, so it is most probable that
the bilateral meeting might take place in the afternoon."
</P>
<P>
There have been signs of improved relations between Pakistan
and India in the past few months. In late March, the two
countries' foreign secretaries resumed their talks after a gap of
three years and their foreign ministers also met last month.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign secretaries' meeting which opened on the Bandos
Island Resort today, Ahmed said they are reviewing the activities
of SAARC during the past year and preparing programs for the next
year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting will also finalize the budget arrangements
for SAARC and determine a new line of directions for SAARC's
relations with international organizations, he said. SAARC has
reached a stage where there is a need to take stock of "what has
been able to be accomplished, what have been the problems and how
we should now look at the future."
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.  
</P>
</TEXT>
