<HEADLINE> Wall Street Plunge Ends Record Run For Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares ended their
record-breaking run today, stymied by a two percent plunge on Wall
Street and pressure from market heavyweight BHP Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Interest rate-sensitive banking and insurance stocks
surrendered recent strong gains following comments by Reserve Bank
of Australia Governor Ian Macfarlane that official rates could
rise if overall wages growth continues.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index sank 12.9 points to 2504.7, while in
New York the Dow Jones industrial average lost 139.7 points to
close at 7085.6.
</P>
<P>
"We were always going to finish lower after Wall street's loss
overnight, and I guess BHP going ex-dividend didn't help matters,"
one trader said.
</P>
<P>
BHP, which went ex-dividend 26 cents, closed 25 cents down.
</P>
<P>
The bank index fell 19.0 points to 4465.0 while the insurance
index dived 96.7 points to 5639.8.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank lost nine cents, Commonwealth Bank shed
eight cents, ANZ was down five while Westpac Bank rose one.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 22.7 points lower at 3936.5,
and the all resources closed 4.9 points down at 1401.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 307.07 million shares worth 801.88
million Australian dollars (629.47 million US dollars).  
</P>
