<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Called For Greater Efforts to Wipe Out Poverty (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress (NPC), who discussed a report on
poverty alleviation today, said that China should increase its
efforts and develop better measures to bring a better life to its
remaining 58 million poverty-stricken people in the final years of
this century.
</P>
<P>
In response to the report by State Councillor Chen Junsheng, a
member of the NPC Standing Committee, Cai Cheng, said: "We must
clearly realize that the remaining number of poor people are a
real difficulty for our national poverty eradication plan, because
they live in extremely difficult and harsh conditions."
</P>
<P>
Other members, Chi Haibin and Xiong Qingquan agreed with Cai in
saying that China has been successful in recent years in helping
the poor, by significantly reducing the number of poor from a
fourth of the world's total, to a twentieth.
</P>
<P>
Chen's ideas about how to deal with this problem in the future
were applauded, but legislators pointed out that, in view of the
different problems in different areas, extra efforts should be
made.
</P>
<P>
Cai said that the government should spend more in villages
where living and production conditions are extremely poor, to
improve conditions necessary for survival and economic
development. Villages where conditions are impossible to alter
should be moved elsewhere and the government should work out
detailed migration plans for impoverished people across the
country, he added.
</P>
<P>
In villages where marriages within the same family are common
and life is made harder by the number of children born
handicapped, the public should be made more aware of relevant laws
and should comply with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
