<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Legislators Debate Growth And Ecology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- At a plenary meeting this afternoon,
China's top legislature listened to a debate on sustainable
development, the ecology and environment, improving northwest
China, and protecting fluorite resources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was presided over by vice-chairman Wu Jieping of
the Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress
(NPC). Lin Zengtang, a NPC Standing Committee member, said that to
maintain growth with Chinese characteristics, China should not
only persist in its family planning policy to encourage families
to have fewer children, but should also strive to improve the
quality of its population.
</P>
<P>
Huang Yicheng, another lawmaker, proposed ways for increasing
water supplies for the desert areas of northwest China, such as
preserving precipitation, exploiting underground water more
carefully, diverting water from the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River, and making artificial rainfall.
</P>
<P>
"The water shortage has been the major obstruction to economic
development in northwest China," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qidong urged the state to reduce export quotas of
fluorite, a mineral that is vital to the metallurgy industry. He
said he also found the waste of this kind of strategic resource
"shocking".
</P>
<P>
Other legislators spoke on poverty relief and protection of
marine resources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
