<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passenger Car Sales Down in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Passenger car sales in the
Philippines continued their downward trend as a total of 6,318
units were sold in April, down by 10.8 percent from 7,086 units in
March.
</P>
<P>
Data released today by the Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers
of the Philippines Inc. showed 27,309 units were sold during the
first four months of this year, compared to 28,638 units during
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The chamber traced the decline to slow processing and selective
approval by some financing companies and institutions of retail
financing applications of prospective buyers.
</P>
<P>
The relocation of the facilities of two assemblers -- Nissan
Motors Phils. Inc. and Toyota Motor Phils. Corp. -- last month
outside Metro Manila may have also adversely affected the
assemblers' productive outputs.
</P>
<P>
The slump could also be due to the fact that some buyers may be
waiting for new models to be introduced by some of the assemblers,
the chamber said.
</P>
<P>
According to the data, total industry sales, which comprise
cars, light commercial vehicles, Asian utility vehicles, trucks
and buses, reached 10,021 units in April from 10,822 in March.
</P>
<P>
Models sold by Mitsubishi Motor Phils, Corp. led the passenger
car market during the month, with 2,838 units sold, compared with
2,754 in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Mitsubishi was followed by Toyota Motors and Columbian Motors
Group with sales of 2,611 units from 3,090 units and 2,422 units
from 2,765 units, respectively, the data indicated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
