<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Firmer Over Job Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar gained ground
today in response to stronger employment figures and Reserve Bank
of Australia Governor Ian Macfarlane's comments ruling out a
near-term cut in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a parliament committee, Macfarlane ruled out a
cut in interest rates to help employment in the coming months,
saying he was concerned that wages growth could be strong enough
to be inflationary.
</P>
<P>
The local dollar closed at 77.85 U.S. cents from 77.59
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
One trader said the short end of the yield curve suffered more
from Macfarlane's comments which had been interpreted as ruling
out the possibility of a rate cut in the near term.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended lower, closing
at 97.11 from 97.36 against the Japanese yen and at 1.3362 from
1.3369 against the Deutsche mark.  
