<HEADLINE> Mobutu Not to Exile in France, French Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The French government today rejected
speculation that Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko will go into
exile in France.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said that
this is not "a topical question."
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old president of Zaire owns a villa in southeastern
France.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations and envoy
for Zaire Bill Richardson discussed the situation in Zaire today
in Paris with Secretary General of the French Foreign Ministry
Bertrand Dufoucq and Director of African affairs Jean-Didier
Roisin on the situation in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Rummelhardt said that the French officials stressed the emergency
situation facing Rwandan refugees stranded in the rebel-controlled
areas, where massacres of the refugees have reportedly taken place.
</P>
<P>
The talks were conducted in "an excellent atmosphere," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was "an occasion for the French as well as the
Americans to confirm that they are aiming the same objectives: a
political solution to the (Zairian) crisis, with a mechanism of
transition conducive to free elections with international
observers," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Mobutu and the presidents of other French-speaking African
countries today began a mini-summit in the Gabonese capital
Libreville on the crisis in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting were Mobutu, Gabonese President Omar
Bongo, Congolese President Pascal Lissouba, Chadian President
Idriss Deby, Central African President Ange-Felix Patasse, and
President Teodoro Obiang Nguema of Equatorial Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The French press reported that the African leaders could
propose the sending of an African peace-keeping force to Kinshasa
to help maintain order during a transitional period in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Zaire's Minister of Information Kin-Kiey Mulumba said that
Mobutu will return to Zaire today or Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
