<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Industrial Production Shows Steady Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Value-added industrial output at the
township level or above in China for April was 174.3 billion yuan,
an 11.9 percent increase over the same period last year, according
to the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
This put the amount for the first four months at 625 billion
yuan, up 11.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises produced 98.6 billion yuan in April, up
6.8 percent, collective enterprises, 53.6 billion yuan, up 14.3
percent, while other sectors produced 37.2 billion worth, up 14.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production for April was as follows:
</P>
<P>
Light and heavy industries increased, amounting to 76.4 billion
yuan and 97.9 billion yuan respectively, increases of 11.9
percent; production and sales were up, with monthly sales
increasing 12.6 percent; major raw materials and processed
materials, including ethylene, synthetic fiber polymers, chemical
fibers, steel products, 10 major nonferrous metals, and aluminum,
increased from 14 to 59.6 percent; crude oil output increased 6.4
percent; and electric output was up 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
But coal production dropped 0.4 percent; and
investment-oriented electronics and machinery products, diesel
engines, machine tools, trucks, and generating equipment declined
from 2.3 to 14.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises running at a loss remain a major problem in China's
industrial economy, and efforts must be made to improve management
and efficiency, experts say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
