<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Set to Ease in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The generally overall inflation
rate will remain below 10 percent in Kenya this year following
the arrival of the long rains last month, the Daily Nation today
quoted a veteran economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, only a rise in real production could bring about an
economic boom in Kenya and curb the inflation rate at the
single-digit level in the election year of 1997, said Maurice
Kanga, the chief economist of the Central Bank of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
The annualized month-on-month inflation rate went up in the
country to 16.1 percent in April from 15.6 percent in March and
11.9 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The annualized inflation rate between January and March
climbed from February's 14.7 percent to 35.6 percent in March,
the highest in the year, then declined to 32.5 percent last
month.
</P>
<P>
The sharp surge in the first quarter was reportedly caused by
the failure of the short rains between October and December,
which brought drought to key growing areas and boosted the prices
of staple foods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some local economists believed Kanga's forecast
was too optimistic, saying investors suffering from election
jitters might defer major investment decisions to next year.
</P>
<P>
Showing the strong impact of drought on inflation, the
unweighted food price index for all income groups rose by 43
percent in the year to March 1997, they say.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the 1996 gross domestic product (GDP) growth was
estimated at 4.6 percent, below the five percent target, they
note, projecting growth this year of six percent.
</P>
<P>
The eastern African country is still haunted by the gross
monetary mismanagement seen in last elections five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The growth in money supply level seen in that one year should
have taken six years to achieve with an average GDP growth rate
of five percent, said Kanga.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot visualize the CBK printing any money. Nobody, even
the bad guys, wants what happened in 1992 to repeat itself," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank's attempt to contain inflation to single
digits by strictly monitoring money supply, analysts said, has
also created a vicious cycle where it competes with banks for
deposits and pushes rates higher. enditem

=05081122

=05081130
NNNN
19:30 19:31 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
