<HEADLINE> Kenyans Wish to Save Local Rice Varieties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Many Kenyan farmers now wish to
have the lost traditional rice varieties re-introduced since the
use of new hybrid seeds has led to a rise in the use of chemical
fertilizer worsening environment extensively.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of hybrid rice has almost completely replaced
the traditional low-yielding rice varieties, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
However, the wide use of chemical fertilizers, which are
necessary for high yield due to new hybrid seeds' weak
resistance to plant diseases, have caused extensive
environmental degradation, destroying flora and fauna through
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Tana River District is such an area where the use of new
varieties of rice has led to the extinction of about 16
varieties of crops, said Dan Kiambi, the International Plant
Genetic Resources Institute (IPGRI) Project Manager.
</P>
<P>
According to IPGRI officials, farmers in the Tana River Delta
used to grow over 60 traditional rice varieties.
</P>
<P>
The clearance of forests, overgrazing, outbreak of forest
fires and drought have all contributed to the loss of traditional
rice varieties in Tana District, Kiambi added.
</P>
<P>
"So far we have collected 220 farmer varieties of rice, we
have decided to regenerate the germ-plasm and conserve them in
the National Gene Bank", he said.
</P>
<P>
Under proper conditions, the different varieties of rice can
be stored for a maximum of 100 years.
</P>
<P>
His center now plans to re-introduce 11 different rice
varieties already extinct in parts of the Tana River Basin. enditem


=05081130

=05081137
NNNN
19:38 19:38 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
