<HEADLINE> Indo-Pak Ties on Way to Improvement: Gujral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister I. K. Gujral
said today that his country's relations with Pakistan are in the
process of improving.
</P>
<P>
Replying questions in the upper house of the parliament here,
Gujral said there has been growing public opinion among
intellectuals in both countries in favor of improved ties.
</P>
<P>
"I am looking forward to meeting my Pakistan counterpart, Nawaz
Sharif, at the next week's summit meeting of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Male," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I assure this house that whatever doctrine we adopt, the issue
of security and integrity of India is non-negotiable," he added.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India,
the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The summit of the seven South Asian nations will be held in the
Maldive capital between May 12 and 14 and the prime ministers of
India and Pakistan are expected to meet on the morning of May 12
to review and discuss their countries' relations and all
outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, leaders of the two countries have expressed
their desire to improve their ties. At the end of March this year
the two countries resumed the foreign secretary-level talks,
stalled in the past three years, and the next round of the talks
will start later this month.  
</P>
