<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-two Tamils, together with
their dinghy, were arrested by the Sri Lankan Navy Wednesday in
the northern sea of the country while they were sailing to South
India, according to security sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said there were 17 males and five females aboard
the dinghy. When interrogated by the security forces, they said
they had paid 15,000 rupees (about 250 U.S. dollars) for each
family to be taken to India.
</P>
<P>
The security forces are still in the process of interrogating
the Tamils in order to get more details, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-nine civilians, who were proceeding to India allegedly
on instructions given by Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels
who have been fighting for a separate Tamil state, were also
arrested by the Sri Lankan Navy last week in the north of the
island.  
