<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Faction Leader Calls for Iraqi Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A Kurdish faction leader in northern
Iraq Jalal Talabani affirmed his opposition to attempts to split
the Kurdish area from Iraq and his support for national unity, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK),
arrived here Saturday night from Iran, weeks after a similar visit
by a delegation from the rival Kurdish Democratic Party (KDP).
</P>
<P>
The PUK and the KDP share control of the autonomous Kurdish
enclave in northern Iraq and have been fighting attempts by
Baghdad to exert its authority over the area.
</P>
<P>
Talabani told MENA today that he discussed with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on Sunday the situation in Iraq and
assured him that Kurds in northern Iraq did not seek separation
from the country.
</P>
<P>
He expressed readiness to negotiate with the Iraqi government,
saying that "a democratic united Iraq will realize the aspirations
of Kurds and Arabs alike in this country."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of Egypt's role in the realization of
national reconciliation in the Kurdish area of Iraq, Talabani said
he reached an understanding with Moussa on the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Dialog with the Iraqi government has reached a dead end since
1991, added Talabani, whose party seeks self-rule in northern Iraq
where 4 million Iraqi Kurds have limited autonomy.
</P>
<P>
He also refuted reports that the PUK received foreign
assistance from any country other than Syrian and some Palestinian
agencies.
</P>
<P>
"We have not received any aid from Israel or any Western
nation," he said, adding that the Iran-PUK relationship is based
on good neighborliness and non-interference.
</P>
<P>
He denied the PUK received Iranian military assistance in the
recent clashes with its main rival KDP, but said Iran extended
humanitarian aid by sheltering 150,000 Kurdish refugees who fled
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has imposed tight security on Talabani, who was
accompanied on his week-long visit here by PUK's senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Egypt took part in the U.S.-led mutilateral forces that drove
Iraq from Kuwait in the 1991 Gulf War and has not restored
diplomatic ties with Iraq since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
