<HEADLINE> Philippines Waives Extra U.S. Sugar Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government today
decided to waive any additional sugar quota to be given by the
United States for the fourth quarter of the 1996-1997 quota year.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to U.S. Agriculture Attache John Wade, Philippine
Sugar Regulatory Administrator Wilson Gamboa said that because of
limited sugar stocks, the country decided to waive whatever
additional U.S. sugar quota it may still have in quota year
1996-1997.
</P>
<P>
But Gamboa assured Wade that the Philippines will "fill up
completely" its regular quota of 250,000 tons for the quota year.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Sugar Board today unanimously agreed to give up
any extra U.S. sugar quota after finding that the country's
remaining sugar stock is apparently inadequate to meet such a
quota, according to Gamboa.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Agriculture is expected to announce next
week an increase in its sugar import for the fourth quarter on
account of low harvest in its sugar-producing states. The
increased amount will be allocated among several countries,
including the Philippines, under a quota system.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is the third largest quota holder under the
U.S. tariff rate quota system for sugar with a share of 13.5
percent, next only to the Dominican Republic and Brazil.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
