<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Changes Likely for Nigeria's Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A major change to Nigeria's transition to
civil rule program was discussed on Wednesday by the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria (NECON) and five political
parties, the Vanguard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The suggested change is that the governorship election originally
set for the last quarter of this year will be postponed to the third
quarter of 1998, to be held on the same day with the presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the national assembly election slated for the
second quarter of next year will be brought forward to the third
quarter of this year and be held on the same day as the state assembly
election.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, however, agreed that the October 1, 1998 hand-over
date will remain irreversibe, a source at the meeting was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the adjustment "is to forestall possible conflict in
the roles of civilian governors under a militray head of state as
wintessed in the ill-fated third republic," the source said. enditem

