<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leap From Appointment to Direct Election for Village Committees (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The ballot tickets were counted: Li
Zhenming, 964 votes, Xu Jianli, 261 votes.
</P>
<P>
Hearing this, 42-year-old Li Zhenming let out a long breath and
felt relieved. His dream of being director of the village
committee had come true.
</P>
<P>
The scene took place in mid-April in Dongxia Village of
Quanzhou City, in southeastern China's coastal Fujian Province. Li
Zhenming became a new director through direct election by local
farmers.
</P>
<P>
The direct election for village committees, which normally
comprised of a director, two deputy directors, and about four
members in a medium-sized village, is held every three years and
has been widespread in China since 1987.
</P>
<P>
"Direct and democratic election is a key political reform in
China's basic-level rural areas, putting an end to village
officials being appointed by township governments," said Wang
Zhenyao, a senior official with the Ministry of Civil Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Following elections for several times in the countryside, the
election procedures tend to become more standard and unified, Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
The universal way is that dozens of villager representatives
are elected prior to the election of village committees.
Preliminary candidates of directors come from the nomination of
such representatives or joint nomination by five or more villagers.
</P>
<P>
And then the villager representative conference will decide the
formal candidates. No organization or individual is allowed to
designate a candidate.
</P>
<P>
In Lishu County of northeast China's Jilin Province, the
candidates are elected directly by all villagers.
</P>
<P>
In many places, the candidates of a village director are
required to give campaign speeches. As to village committee
members, there are more candidates than the actual number.
</P>
<P>
The final balloting is usually held in either a large square or
several separate balloting stations. Whatever the method, there
are secret balloting rooms to fend off the intervention of
others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leap From Appointment to Direct Election for Village Committees (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fujian Province has been taking the lead in the country with
regard to the standard election methods in the rural areas. Such
elections began in the mid-1980s, and the sixth round of election
will have been completed by the end of November this year.
</P>
<P>
With 1,463 voters, Dongxia Village of Quanzhou City began
preparations for the election at the end of March. In accordance
with the law on electing village committees, 25 villager
representatives were elected.
</P>
<P>
Early in April, nominations by the representatives and groups
of villagers produced four preliminary candidates for directors,
together with 18 preliminary candidates for deputy directors and
village committee members.
</P>
<P>
In the following selection conference, the four preliminary
candidates of directors delivered their campaign speeches,
explaining to the public their detailed plans on managing village
affairs.
</P>
<P>
One of the candidates, who had several private businesses
including a furniture plant and a food store, was believed to be
an active person in the village. Because of this, the villagers
thought that he might spend too little energy handling village
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Being viewed as inexperienced and indecisive, another candidate
was not able to win the trust of most villagers. In this way, the
two persons were screened out after balloting at the villager
representative conference.
</P>
<P>
Both the remaining two formal candidates of directors had good
plans for village management. Li Zhenming used to run a crafts
factory and shoe-making plant, and he was enthusiastic about the
public affairs and ready to help others.
</P>
<P>
The other formal candidate, Xu Jianli, 33, also put forward his
plan to boost the village economy, and promised to make new
achievements for the villager's welfare and the village
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rainstorms Hit Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains attacked Hong Kong
this morning, causing road flooding, landslide, traffic congestion
and suspension of classes.
</P>
<P>
At 10:25 am today, local observatory announced the first
rainstorm red warning so far this year, indicating that more than
50 millimeters of rain had fallen generally across Hong Kong over
the past hour.
</P>
<P>
The most severely stricken area was Tsuen Wan in the northwest
of the New Territories, where 150 millimeters of rainfall were
recorded during the two hours between nine and eleven o'clock in
the morning. In most parts of the Kowloon Peninsula rainfall
exceeded 100 millimeters.
</P>
<P>
Rainstorms led to road flooding, land sinking, landslide and
traffic congestion in many places in Kowloon and the New
Territories. Five landslides were reported this morning, with four
in Tsuen Wan and one in Sai Kung in the northeast of the New
Territories, said the Government Information Service.
</P>
<P>
Kindergartens, primary and middle schools all suspended classes
this afternoon, employers were reminded of employees' safety in
workplace and their journey to and from work when a rainstorm
warning is in force, hotlines were opened for the public to report
any flooding to concerned government departments.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Observatory forecast continued heavy rain in the
next a few days when an unstable southerly air storm remains to
affect the South China coastal region.
</P>
<P>
The sub-tropical climate usually brings Hong Kong thunderstorms
and heavy rains in May to August every year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
