<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afforestation Helps Protect Ancient Great Wall (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, May 8 (Xinhua) -- At the edge of the Mu Us desert,
northwest China, the Great Wall had long remained buried by sand
and wind.
</P>
<P>
With local farmers' effort to build a "green great wall," one
of the world's ecological wonders, however, the ancient Chinese
monument is miraculously growing "taller and taller". And a couple
meters are visible above the heavy yellow sand.
</P>
<P>
For the last couple of years, Bai Chunlan, a farmer from
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region and her fellow
villagers have been working on reclaiming this area from the
desert, just like their ancestors who had constructed the Great
Wall with brick and clay in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
With their effort to plant forests and grass, the "green
great wall" has not only helped improve the ecology of the area,
but also helped effectively protect the ancient remains of the
Great Wall zigzaging through the vast desert.
</P>
<P>
In Shabianzi Village of Yanchi County, Ningxia, which literally
means "Desert's Edge," less than a score of households stayed on
because of the advancement of sand six years ago. Desert has not
only destroyed local people's homes, but also damaged ancient
cultural relics. Many villagers moved to other places seeking for
better life, Bai said.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Administration of Cultural Relics, the
ancient remains of the Great Wall in nine provinces and autonomous
regions in north and northwest China have an aggregate length of
50,000 km, but the current length of the remains available only
totals about 10,000 km owing to the ravages of wind, rain, and
sand.
</P>
<P>
To combat the desert, Bai Chunlan shifted her home eight km
away from the village in a donkey-driven cart together with her
husband. Nothing was growing except an old elm tree. She was 30
years old then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leap From Appointment to Direct Election for Village Committees (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the mid-April final election participated by all voters of
the village, Li Zhenming, who won a high percentage of votes, was
elected director of the village committee. The other members of
the committee were also chosen through multi-candidate election.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jianli lost the election and "felt something of pity," but
conceded that "the election reflected the wishes of the
villagers."
</P>
<P>
"I respect the villagers' choice, and I'll try to be elected
director next time," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Wu Yapeng, an official with the Quanzhou City
Civil Affairs Bureau, four rounds of direct elections for village
committees have been conducted since 1987.
</P>
<P>
The elections were well organized, villagers had a high degree
of participation, and the elections became more and more standard,
Wu said.
</P>
<P>
The building of rural democracy has made two leaps over the
past dozen years: one is from traditional appointment to election,
and the other is from indirect election to direct election, said
Zhang Xiaogan, a senior official with the Fujian Provincial Civil
Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the scope of the whole country, however, there
still exist some problems in one form or another. Some local
officials tend to put off such elections without cause. And in one
village, some villagers tear apart the list of candidates not to
their liking, according to a Civil Affairs Ministry official.
</P>
<P>
"There has to be a process of gradual improvement in grassroot
democracy. After all, China's villages have taken the key step on
the road to democracy," the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afforestation Helps Protect Ancient Great Wall (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The efforts to harness desert and sand proved a tough job, said
Bai. On the desert, people could hardly stand when a strong wind
blew. And the young trees just planted were often pulled out from
the root.
</P>
<P>
Bai and her husband got up early every day, replanted young
trees just pulled out, rescued young trees buried in the sand, and
irrigated them with water from a well some 15 km away.
</P>
<P>
Bai also planted on a trial basis 0.2 hectares of wheat, which
produced no grain at all after the wheat was buried in the sand.
</P>
<P>
"The government sent us grass seeds and saplings, and
dispatched scientific workers to help us as well," said Bai.
Saplings that take root in the drift sand dunes eventually grow
green leaves.
</P>
<P>
By now, Bai's family has grown 16,000 trees, and planted 83.3
hectares of sand-grown shrubs and grass. The trees earn the Bais
an annual income of 24,000 yuan. The family now live in a bungalow
house with four separate rooms. In the back courtyard, cattle and
sheep thrive.
</P>
<P>
Bai Chunlan, awarded "March 8" green medal and cited as a
national role model, was received by central government leaders at
the Great Hall of the People last year, to commend her
contributions to protecting the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
In view of the sand-harnessing efforts that have helped
protect the Great Wall, government departments decided to build a
farm around the forests Bai has planted.
</P>
<P>
The Huangshawo (yellow sand area) where only one elm tree grew
is now not only a home to the farm, but also to a new village of
12 households, with birds singing merrily in the groves and sheep
grazing leisurely in the fenced pasture.
</P>
<P>
The administrative village of Shabianzi, now with more than 200
rural households, have planted 1,333 hectares of trees and grass
at the farm, and have reclaimed desert land to grow rice,
cultivate fish, and build sties for rearing livestocks, according
to village head Li Fengqi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afforestation Helps Protect Ancient Great Wall (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The effort of Bai and her friends have repaid. Dong Yaohui,
secretary-general of the China Great Wall Association, said that
the construction of the "green great wall" has helped effectively
protect the ancient Great Wall in Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
Dong quoted results of an official inspection as saying that
the 178-km Great Wall of the Ming Dynasty in Yanchi County,
Ningxia, has regained its past grandeur and is considered as one
of the best preserved sections of the Great Wall, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Xinmin, director of Lanzhou Desert Institute
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, China has planted trees and
grass on 9.15 million hectares of the country's desert border
regions, reducing wind speed of the respective regions by 70
percent and enormously controling the advancement of sand.
</P>
<P>
In Shapuotou, Zhongwei County of Ningxia, on the verge of
Tengger Desert where the Great Wall also passes through, farmers
with Gusha Forest Farm have built a 60-km-long green corridor over
the past 40 years, which has ensured safe operations of the
Baotou-Lanzhou Railway Line, the country's first desert railway
line.
</P>
<P>
The forest farm has thus been awarded a prize for best
environmental protection by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
As more trees are grown, animals that had long disappeared have
started to return to the forest farm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing-Kowloon Express Runs Soon (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A luxurious passenger train linking
Beijing with Kowloon will be in service from May 18, thus ending
the absence of direct trains between the Chinese capital and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Every other day, the 97/98 train will set out from the Beijing
West Railway Station to reach Kowloon in 29 hours and 40 minutes,
with stopovers at major cities such as Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou,
Xinyang, Wuchang, Changsha, Hengyang, Shaoguan and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The train, with all carriages being sleepers, will use the
newly-built 25K type passenger cars, which are considered the most
deluxe made in China.
</P>
<P>
The train is the first domestic run to have a deluxe carriage
of two-person soft-sleeper compartments, which have only been
available on international routes.
</P>
<P>
"The train, the result of cooperation between relevant
departments in inland areas and Hong Kong, will provide prompt
handling of exit and entry procedures and first-class service, an
official of the Beijing Railway Administration told a press
conference held today.
</P>
<P>
The team serving the train is made up of 250 carefully-selected
personnel who have received special training in service standards,
and in language skills in Mandarin, Guangdong dialect, and
English.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
