<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Adopt International Maritime Travel Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine National Economic and
Development Authority has approved the adoption of the
international maritime travel rules to simplify documentary
requirements for ships engaged in international voyages.
</P>
<P>
The authority will start a formal evaluation of the country's
position which the Department of Foreign Affairs can use as a
basis for seeking a Senate ratification, the Philippine News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1965 International Conference on Facilitation of
Maritime Travel and Transport Convention, foreign ships are
required to submit only eight documents to gain clearance.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is presently requiring 13 documents from
vessels which travel abroad, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Once the convention is approved by the Senate, the country has
to reduce the number of required documents and revise some
sections in the Tariff and Customs Code of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The sections require presentation of inward foreign manifest,
storage plan, bills of landing, clearance from last port of call
and the oath of master of entering vessel.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Ports Authority said the country will benefit
from the Senate's ratification of the convention despite the need
to change several policies.
</P>
<P>
The convention reduces the number of documents which public
authorities can demand of a ship and adopts standardized forms for
maritime travel.
</P>
<P>
The measure also seeks to avoid delays in shipment which have
been frequently cited as a costly burden by the maritime sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
