<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Proposed Health Fee for Foreigners Causes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A proposed bill by Kuwaiti
Health Ministry to impose an annual health fee on expatriates has
caused wide resentment among foreign workers here.
</P>
<P>
The Arab Times today quoted expatriates as describing the
proposed annual charge of 50 Kuwaiti dinars (165 U.S. dollars) as
"unjustified, unfair and unreasonable," saying it should not be
made mandatory.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports had said the Kuwaiti Ministry of Health was
currently negotiating with four local insurance companies to carry
out the mandatory health insurance scheme designed only for
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Some expatriates said if the scheme was imposed, they would
leave the country for good, because the scheme would overburden
their strained finances.
</P>
<P>
A cleaning worker said "this 50 KD is too high for me since it
is more than my monthly income," adding that "If the draft law is
implemented, there will be no point of me staying here any
longer."
</P>
<P>
The bill is yet to be approved by the cabinet and the
National Assembly to become law.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Kuwait was in a drive to gradually
increase the rate of nationals in the whole labor force, and the
newly proposed health fee scheme was aimed at encouraging
employers to hire more Kuwaitis.
</P>
<P>
This move is also part of the efforts by the government to
solve the potential unemployment of the Gulf country, they said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently has 1.25 million expatriates, almost double
the number of its own population of 710,000 people.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the proposed insurance fee is also said to help
increase the health ministry's income as well as to get rid of the
misuse of free health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
