<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The court of appeal of Versailles Wednesday
ordered the Renault automaker to stop the process of closing its
Vilvoorde assembly plant in Belgium, saying it didn't consult with
its European workers committee beforehand.
</P>
<P>
-- Numerous diplomatic efforts are going on today in Libreville
and Paris in search of a solution to the Zairian crisis. Several
heads of French-speaking African countries are meeting today in
Libreville, while U.S. envoy for Zaire, Bill Richardson, will meet
with President Jacques Chirac in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South African Vice President Thabo Mbeki announced
that President Mobutu Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent-Desire
Kabila will meet again on May 14 in an unspecified place.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- After President Jacques Chirac published his article
Wednesday appealing for support from the French people, the
leaders of the center-right majority expressed satisfaction, while
the opposition Socialists and Communists criticized the
intervention by the president as "nothing new."
</P>
<P>
-- Two European airspace groups, the British Aerospace and the
German Daimler-Benz Aerospace, announced on Wednesday their
exclusive support to French defense-media group Lagardere's
bidding to take over the state defense electronics giant Thomson
CSF.
</P>
<P>
The Lagardere group therefore represents a European option when
rivaling its duo-competitor of Alcatel Alsthom electronics group and
Dassault Industrie aeronautics group, which also want to buy Thomson
CSF from the French state. 
</P>
