<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Foreign Secretaries Meet in Maldives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MALE, the Maldives, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC)
comprising foreign secretaries of the seven member countries
started a two-day meeting today at the Bandos Island Resort near
here.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC Standing Committee, which plays an important role in
the policy-making of the regional organization, is expected to
prepare for the agenda and programs of the coming session of the
Council of Ministers and the ninth SAARC summit to be held in the
country later this month.
</P>
<P>
According to SAARC Secretary-General Naeem Hasan, the summit,
the highest authority of the association, will discuss a wide
range of issues, with poverty eradication and economic and trade
cooperation top on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretaries of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka are attending the 23rd
session of the Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Naeem Hasan, delivering a statement at the session, expressed
the hope that the meeting would make a significant contribution to
enhancing regional cooperation by adding a new direction of its
own and infusing greater dynamism to the SAARC process.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee is reviewing a report prepared by the
SAARC Programming Committee composed of senior officials of the
member countries at the 2-day session which ended at the Bandos
Island Resort on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Programming Committee finalized the reports submitted by
various SAARC technical committees for communications, education,
culture and sports, health, tourism, population activities and
child welfare, and discussed the reports of the Governing Boards
and Budgets of SAARC Regional Centers.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was established in December 1985 to accelerate the
process of economic and social development in member states
through joint action in agreed areas of cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
