<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Meets HK Entrepreneurs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Wang Fengchao, deputy director of
the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, met
here today with a delegation from the Business and Professionals
Federation of Hong Kong led by its Chairman Lo Hong-sui.
</P>
<P>
Wang said there are 54 days left before the return of Hong Kong
to the embrace of the motherland, and the general situation of
Hong Kong is very good, and the most of the people there wish for
a smooth transition and the prosperity and stability of the region.
</P>
<P>
This is also the goal of the State Council, especially its Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In the following 50-plus days, Wang said, "we will carry out
work for the maintenance of the stable transition and the smooth
transfer of power, so as to make Hong Kong more stable and
prosperous after 1997, and create good conditions for the
establishment of the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region on July 1 and its effective work afterwards."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of how the people in the interior areas
get approval to go to Hong Kong, Wang said the Basic Law has made
clear stipulations in this regard.
</P>
<P>
After 1997, people in other places of China must go through a
strict procedure of approval to enter the Hong Kong SAR, he said.
The number of the people to go there will be decided by the
relevant department of the central people's government after
consulting the SAR government, he added.
</P>
<P>
In order to maintain the prosperity and stability of Hong Kong
after 1997, we will implement a strict procedure of approval on
those in the interior areas to go to Hong Kong to see relatives,
to pay a visit, or to get settled there, in accordance with the
regulations, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Wang assured the people that there will not be the case of
large numbers of people in the interior areas moving to Hong Kong
after its return.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wang conferred with the guests on such issues as
the rights of permanent residency for the non-Chinese residents in
Hong Kong, and the participation of the Hong Kong business people
in the development of the central and western areas of China.
</P>
<P>
He also introduced the Hong Kong visitors on how the work goes
to negotiate with foreign countries on visa-free access for the
SAR passport holders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
