<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Cypriot Children in Poor Fitness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Children in Cyprus are in poor
fitness standards with massive cholesterol and overweight problem,
according to a study on local children's health and diet,
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The study, carried out by Dr. Michalis Tornaritis who tested
800 children in the Nicosia area, the Cypriot capital, shows just
over half of them -- 52 percent -- have cholesterol levels above the
highest acceptable mark predisposing them to chronic diseases.
</P>
<P>
Girls were reported to be the plumper of the two sexes, with
57 percent of them overweight, compared to 39 percent of the boys
tested.
</P>
<P>
Poor dietary habits and lack of exercise are the cause of the
problem, the report says.
</P>
<P>
It adds that the children's physical state indicates very poor
fitness levels, with 54 percent of boys and 36 percent of girls
unable to meet acceptable levels.
</P>
<P>
The report stresses that if these problems are not dealt with
now, these children will face serious health problems in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Parents are informed of their children's physical condition
and advised on how to improve their health standards.
</P>
<P>
According to Tornaritis, as part of the "Children's Health"
program launched by the health ministry, educational seminars are
now being held for parents and teachers to advise them on correct
dietary habits for their children as well as the importance of
exercise.
</P>
<P>
The program will now be extended to all elementary schools
across the island, with over 11,000 sixth grade children being
tested. Follow-up tests will be carried out on the children after
three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
