<HEADLINE> Manila Likely Not to Import Yellow Corn: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Because of the time constraint in
completing the internal procedural requirements, the Philippines
may have no time to import 350,000 tons of yellow corn as
requested by the country's hog farmers, a senior food official
said today.
</P>
<P>
The National Food Authority (NFA) agreed last month to import
350,000 tons of yellow corn to meet a shortage in the domestic
market, NFA chief Joemari Gerochi told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But Gerochi said this planned importation has so far failed to
get approval of the Cabinet. The corn imports will also need to be
endorsed by President Fidel Ramos and finally the Congress.
</P>
<P>
Gerochi said if the internal procedural requirements could be
completed by the middle of this month, the country will still have
time to import yellow corn from the United States or its neighbor
China.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he said, the plan to import yellow corn will have to
be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
According to Gerochi, all the importation of the 350,000 tons
of yellow corn should be completed by June because the country's
corn harvest starts in July.
</P>
<P>
Due to increasing corn requirements of the livestock industry,
the Philippines will have to import about 500,000 to 800,000 tons
of corn this year to meet a corn shortfall.
</P>
<P>
The country imported some 120,000 metric tons of yellow corn
from China in February and over 20,000 tons of white corn from
another country last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
