<HEADLINE> Chinese Delegation Arrives in Pusan for EAG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese athletes were required to
have their best forms for upcoming East Asian Games, according to
the Chinese delegation here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation, which arrived here Thursday afternoon in
chilly winds and drizzles, were led by Olympic gold medalists lifters
Tang Lingsheng and Zhan Xugang.
</P>
<P>
Tang Lingsheng claimed the title in the 59kg category and Zhan
Xugang had the crown and set three world records in the 70kg division.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wen, spokeswoman for the Chinese delegation, told Xinhua that
all Chinese athletes were demanded to get everything ready in the
shortest time for the games.
</P>
<P>
"Chief-de-Mission Wu Shouzhang has asked all members to take part
in the games with their best forms," Wen Wen said.
</P>
<P>
At the first East Asian Games in Shanghai in 1993, China, with home
advantage, had 105 golds to lead the medal tally. Japan and South
Korea were second and third with 25 and 23 golds respectively.
</P>
<P>
Competing on road this time, China is also determined to finish
atop in the team standings.
</P>
<P>
In order to reach the goal, China has sent several Olympic gold
medal winners for the games, including women judoka Sun Fuming, who
took the first title for China in Atlanta last summer.
</P>
<P>
Another objective to patcipate in the games for China, according to
Wu Shaozhang, is to take the games as a warm-up for the Asian Games in
1998 and 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
"Through East Asian Games, we should have a better understandings
of our rivals and ourselves," Wu said. 
</P>
