<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Agrarian Reform Program Endangered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government's
Comprehensive Agrarian Reform Program (CARP) is heading for a
virtual collapse due to lack of support services, the official
Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only one-third of the total lands acquired by the
government under the reform program have been given support
services, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Support services are infrastructure items such as roads,
bridges, water sources, and ecologically balanced structures,
which assure the production and marketing of agricultural
products.
</P>
<P>
Since early 1990s, the government began to implement the
agrarian reform program under which it purchases lands from
landlords and then apportions them to landless farmers.
</P>
<P>
As of January last year, the Department of Agrarian Reform
acquired some 2.5 million hectares of agricultural lands all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
But of the 2.5 million hectares of acquired lands, only about
33 percent got the needed support services, the agency said. The
rest is turning into "useless" agricultural lands because of lack
of support services, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
