<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Official Warns of More Violence in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior United States official
warned here today that any further delay in resuming peace
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians could lead to
more violence in the region, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The official, who is close to the visiting U.S. Middle East
Envoy Dennis Ross and speaking on condition of anonymity, made the
remarks as Ross' shuttle diplomacy between the Israeli and
Palestinian sides entered the second day.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived here Wednesday, hoping for a new U.S. initiative
that might break the two-month impasse in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Media reports said Ross brings proposals that include
tradeoffs such as an Israeli freeze on settlement construction
and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
resuming the sharing of intelligence information, which was cut
off in March.
</P>
<P>
Ross made no comment as he entered Israeli Prime Minister's
Office Wednesday night for talks with Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official said that the violent confrontation between
Israel and the Palestinians following the beginning of the
construction at Har Homa would return if there is no progress in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Ross is to meet with Arafat and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak today, after meetings with Israeli President Ezer Weizman,
Netanyahu, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, and Foreign
Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between the two sides stalled in March
after Israel started to build a controversial new Jewish
neighborhood at Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim) on the southeastern
outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have said that Israel must stop the construction
before talks can resume, while Israel insists that the PNA crack
down on terror and reestablish full security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Senior Netanyahu aide David Bar-Ilan said Wednesday he
expected Ross's presence would lead to progress.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever Ross is here there is some movement in the peace
process and it is usually positive," Bar-Ilan said, while
cautioning against expecting a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Ross's visit comes a day after Weizman met with Arafat at the
Erez checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
After that meeting, Weizman said Arafat agreed to resume
contacts between senior security officials, but the Palestinians
conditioned this on the presence of U.S. officials at all
meetings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
