<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, May 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnian Serb army's Chief of General Staff Pero
Colic Wednesday accused Muslim forces of preparing a massive
attack on Serbian territories in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Colic said in an interview published by a Belgrade-based
evening newspaper that the reliable intelligence information had
suggested that the Muslim army now is making all-round
preparations for the attack on Serbs and the occupation of Serbian
territories in coming August.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- The United Nations should withdraw the Multinational
Protection Force (MPF) from Albania if the national reconciliation
government headed by Prime Minister Bashkim Fino falls, Italian
Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He told the Lower House that if the Fino government fell,
normal life would no longer exist in the war-torn country. In this
case, the United Nations should reconsider the task or even
withdraw the Italian-led MPF. Italy and the other countries in the
mission were seeking to increase understanding between the
Albanian parties and enable elections to be held at the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- More than 180 lawmakers Wednesday formed an unofficial
group aimed at preventing Ukraine from joining NATO. The group,
called "Ukraine outside NATO", warned in a statement that joining
the Western alliance would "pull our country into a fratricidal
war with neighboring states".
</P>
<P>
There is broad opposition to NATO membership in Ukraine. The
group was formed on the day when visiting NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana handed to President Leonid Kuchma a draft document
outlining a special partnership with the former Soviet bloc.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has pledged recently
in a letter to the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan
that Russia will abide by the international treaty banning
chemical arms.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that the main obstacle in the way to ratifying the
treaty was the problem of money needed to destroy the country's
chemical weapons. Russia is among the signatories of the Chemical
Weapons Convention, which came into effect on April 29, but the
Russian parliament has failed to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Newly-elected members of the British parliament swore
in on Wednesday, with Betty Boothroyd re-elected speaker of the
House of Commons. This was the first sitting of parliament since
the May 1 election when Tony Blair's Labor Party stormed into
power with an overall majority of 179.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The FBI of the United States is investigating
whether a senior U.S. government official has been providing
sensitive information to Israel, the Washington Post said on
Wednesday. The FBI launched the investigation in January after the
National Security Agency intercepted a secure communication
between a senior Israeli intelligence officer in Washington and a
superior in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia hopes that Spain will take into account
Russia's position on NATO's eastward expansion plan during the
discussion of these issues in the Alliance, Russian Deputy Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov said on Wednesday at a joint press conference
with visiting Spanish Foreign Minister Abel Matutes y Juan. He
also noted that Russia outlined its vision of the future European
security system.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Visiting British new Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said
here on Wednesday that London wished to start a new era of
cooperative relations between the leading members of the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
"We're determined to draw a line under the sterile and negative
confrontation of the past," said Cook at a news conference after
talks with his German counterpart, Klaus Kinkel, Wednesday
afternoon. It was the maiden overseas visit by Cook since he took
office last week. Before coming to Bonn, Cook had also paid a
visit to Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
