<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Businesses Asked to Develop Wariness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese foreign trade
official called for businesses in China to be more wary of risks
when they make investments abroad to avoid major losses.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the lack of knowledge of common practices, laws, and
regulations of foreign countries, and that of the investment
projects, foreign partners and competitors, many Chinese
businesses have been "badly deceived" in foreign markets, and some
of them have even been sued or sentenced to pay large sum of
money, or their parent companies were affected, said Liu
Xiangdong, assistant minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He told a seminar on global risk management that in order to
sharpen their competitiveness and increase their self-protection,
Chinese enterprises should make correct decisions while investing
overseas by getting familiar with international common practices,
constantly collecting the latest information of relevant markets,
seeking reliable partners, and understanding local laws and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
With the deepening of China's reform and open-up, many Chinese
businesses have invested in foreign manufacturing and trade
enterprises and the futures market.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the Chinese Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation will strengthen both management and service
for Chinese businesses' investment abroad.
</P>
<P>
At today's seminar, which was sponsored by the MOFTEC and the
Kroll Associates of the United States, experts from the latter
introduced techniques on how to gain knowledge of partners,
clients, competitors, and markets before the deal, how to avoid
the abnormal situations after the investment, and how to deal with
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1972, Kroll is one of the first-rated risk managment
and consultancy firms. It set up its Beijing office in March last
year, and it now has 21 offices across the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
