that Japan faces a tough road for its mission as bowling is penciled
up as a demonstration sport.
</P>
<P>
"The level of the games might be higher than the first Shanghai
East Asian Games and will certainly be very competitive, so we must
do
our best and want to gain more medals than the first games," said the
Chef de Mission.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugural meet, Japan ranked only next to China with 25
golds, 37 silvers and 55 bronzes, beating South Korea to third at 23
golds, 28 silvers and 40 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to bag home medals from the sports of athletics,
gymnastics, judo, soft tennis and the team games of soccer and
basketball," said Yoshiro.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, we are to gain 26 golds but the pre-set goal remains
uncertain as we don't know the entry lists of other delegations," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
For the Pusan Games, Japan has dispatched a 397-member squad for
14
sports, including 279 athletes.
</P>
<P>
As a testing ground for the coming major international games,
"Japan has sent off new generation for the sports of basketball,
gymnastics, weightlifting and wrestling while our best athletes will
compete in the events of athletics, soccer and judo," he said.
</P>
<P>
On his behalf, Choe Hyun-yol, South Korean Chef de Mission, said
the host will spare no efforts and exploit its home advantage to take
over Japan in the medal tally as his athletes enjoy upperhands in
Taekwondo, Judo, Boxing and Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
However, both Japan and South Korea refrained from voicing their
intention to challenge China that garnered a dominating bag of 213
medals including 105 golds from the first edition.
</P>
<P>
For the fortnight Pusan Games, Kazakhstan replaces DPR Korea that
decides to skip the second edition which features the same roster of
China, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, Macao, Chinese Taipei, Mongolia
and Guam.
</P>
