<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blood Donation in Beijing to Commemorate World Red Cross Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Beijing opened blood donation
centers in its 18 districts and counties today to mark May 8th,
the World Red Cross Day.
</P>
<P>
"It is the 15th time for the city to hold such large-scale
blood donation," said Li Xueming, director of the city's Office of
Blood Donation, who was among the first group of volunteers to
donate blood today.
</P>
<P>
Li said since the publicity campaign of free blood donation
began in Beijing in 1984, about 260,000 people have donated their
blood. There were more than 80,000 blood donors in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the time the activity ended this morning, about 400 people
donated a total of 79,000 ml of blood, according to the donation
office.
</P>
<P>
Voluntary donation is a safer and more efficient way for blood
collection, compared to blood-selling and compulsory donation,
said Sui Baiqiu, executive vice-chairman of the Chinese Red Cross
Society.
</P>
<P>
But donated blood only makes up a small proportion of the total
amount of blood for clinical use in China, she added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the blood for clinical use in the
country surpassed 1,000 tons last year, which was collected from
five million people. But only five percent of the blood came from
unpaid donors, while 35 percent was collected through compulsory
donation.
</P>
<P>
Sun said that a draft law on the introduction of a free blood
donation system was submitted to the Standing Committee of the
Eighth National People's Congress for examination.
</P>
<P>
The law would help promote free blood donation in the country,
if adopted by the country's top legislature, she added.
</P>
<P>
Many countries and regions in the world have achieved the goal
that all the blood for clinical use is collected through free
blood donation.
</P>
<P>
China, Laos, Vietnam and the Philippines are the only ones
among the 17 countries and regions in the Pacific region that
still rely on paid blood contribution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
