<HEADLINE> Sydney Cost up to Four Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The cost of the 2000 Sydney Olympic
Games will be at least 5.2 billion Australian dollars (4.04
billion US dollars), according to the Sydney Organising Committee
for the Olympic Games (SOCOG) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The cost is up 43 percent comparing with the original estimates
made four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, SOCOG are still forecasting a modest surplus. New
South Wales (NSW) Olympics Minister Michael Knight said the
substantial changes in the budget for SOCOG, were due to the
lessons learned from the Centennial Olympic Games in Atlanta last
summer.
</P>
<P>
"We've got a budget which is much more realistic than the bid
budget. It's the difference between planning and doing," he said.
</P>
<P>
While SOCOG's spending was up sharply from the original budget,
revenue has also increased sharply from 1.26 billion U.S. dollars
to 1.81 billion.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG's budget is mainly generated from sponsorships,
television rights fees, tickets and marketing deals and does not
draw on the public purse.
</P>
<P>
SOCOG also released for the first time information on the size
of the salaries of its senior executives, which showed the top
eight staff earn between 194,500 and 350,000 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
