<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Officials Warn Against Foreign Businesses' Tariff Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Some foreign businesses are evading
customs duties on imports by declaring lower purchasing prices
than they actually offered, Customs officials in eastern China's
Zhejiang province say.
</P>
<P>
Most of tax-evaders were solely foreign-funded ventures and
processing industries of imported materials, because the nation
abolished the tax exemption for foreign-funded ventures that
imported equipment and raw materials, according to an official
with the Provincial Administration for the Inspection of Import
and Export Commodities.
</P>
<P>
"This not just ate away the state revenues from the import
business, some ventures also imported more equipment and raw
materials than the official quota they were allowed through the
same trick," he said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the past tax evasion trick of declaring higher
prices of the imports and passing shoddy goods for quality ones,
the new practice can do harm no less, said Customs officials.
</P>
<P>
"It not only contravened the normal work order of attracting
foreign investment and went against the principle of fair trade,
but also resulted in a severe drain of state revenue," said a
Customs official.
</P>
<P>
As a new measure against the tax evasion, foreign businesses
are required to hand over a deposit to guarantee against declaring
import prices lower than actual prices, and to pay taxes after
strict inspection and evaluation of the goods are conducted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
