<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges Universal Adherence to Chemical Weapons Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese delegate today
called on all members of the international community to join the
implementation of a treaty banning all chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Manli, head of the Chinese delegation and ambassador to the
Netherlands, elaborated China's position on the issue at the first
session of the Conference of State Parties to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Effective from April 29, the treaty is formerly known as the
Convention on the Prohibition of the Development, Production,
Stockpiling and Use of Chemical Weapons and on Their Destruction.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted the key to the success of activities related to the
document, popularly known as the Chemical Weapons Convention, or
CWC, laid in part in the achievement of its universality.
</P>
<P>
The CWC's purpose and principles can be achieved at an early
date "only when all the members of the international community
actively participate in and support" its implementation, she said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the Chinese official appealed to the countries which
have not ratified the Convention, particularly those possessing
chemical weapons, to approve the document as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
As an original signatory of the treaty, she noted, China has
always stood for the total elimination of all types of weapons of
mass destruction, and has made unremitting efforts for this end.
</P>
<P>
"A victim itself to chemical weapons in the past," Zhu said,
China has always advocated their "complete prohibition and
thorough destruction," and has had great concerns over abandoned
chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
She called it "most disturbing" that the chemical weapons
abandoned on China's territory are still posing a grave threat to
the lives and property of the Chinese people and the ecological
environment.
</P>
<P>
Thus, she said, China strongly demands the concerned country to
show an attitude of being responsible for history and fulfill the
obligations under the Convention by cleaning up the weapons.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing the indispensability of the verification regime to
the CWC's effectiveness, the official stressed that China was
strongly opposed to any act of abusing the Convention's
verification provisions to jeopardize China's sovereignty and
security.
</P>
<P>
"Any such abuse will certainly undermine the effectiveness and
universality of the Convention," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
She pledged that China would continue to take part, with a
positive attitude, in the work of the Organization for the
Prohibition of Chemical Weapons to achieve an early realization of
the objectives and principles of the Convention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0202 </DOCNO>
