<HEADLINE> China's Electronic Exports Surging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, China's exports
of electronic products will double the 1997 figure to 35 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China exported 18.4 billion dollars worth-of such products last
year, according to Li Yuxiang, director of Economic Operations and
Restructuring Department of the Ministry of the Electronic
Industry who was here for an inspection tour.
</P>
<P>
The exports consisted mainly of computers and accessories,
household electrical appliances, and basic equipment for the
electronic industry. The export of electronic commodities made up
38 percent of China's total exports of machinery and electronic
products.
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, the country's electronic industrial output
value increased at an annual rate of 27 percent. China generated
300 billion yuan of electronic industrial output value in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The country's electronic output value is projected to amount to
somewhere between 700 billion 1,000 billion yuan in the year 2000,
said Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
