<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysian-African Ties Growing Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad returned home today after a week-long visit to
three southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's visit to the Republic of Malawi, Botswana and South
Africa not only strengthened ties between Malaysia and these
African countries but also succeeded in wooing businessmen of
these countries to form partnerships with Malaysian investors.
</P>
<P>
His visit facilitated the understanding of each other's
potentials and resources, paving the way for more business
cooperation between the private sectors of Malaysia and the three
African countries.
</P>
<P>
In Malawi, Mahathir attended a business forum, which marked the
beginning of a new era for business collaboration between
Malaysian and Malawian businessmen with the two sides signing
agreements to build highways and upgrade existing roads.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian company, G-Two Holdings Berhad (Ltd.), will
undertake the mammoth project. It will also build a 3 billion
ringgit (about 1.2 billion U.S. dollars) new satellite township in
Blantyre, Malawi, besides a 70 million ringgit (about 28 million
U.S. dollars) international standard hotel.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's biggest telecommunication company, Telekom Malaysia
Berhad has also set foot in Malawi through its joint venture with
the Malawi Post and Telecommunication Corporation in Telekom
Network Limited.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of Mahathir's visit, more Malaysian companies are
expected to go to Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir continued his business opportunity exploring mission
in Botswana, where he met with the local businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The business delegation which accompanied Mahathir took the
opportunity to scout for possible joint ventures with their
counterparts in Botswana although there were no agreements signed
between the two countries during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Also in Botswana, Mahathir took the center stage at the first
Southern Africa International Dialogue in Kasane, where he
delivered a special address to 12 African leaders, stressing the
need for the southern African sub-region to form a smart
partnership to face the challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was also asked to share his views on Malaysia's
success story.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, the last leg of his mission, Mahathir was
honored for his "exceptional and invaluable contribution" to the
promotion of friendly and mutually beneficial relations between
the African republic and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He received South Africa's highest award "the Order of Good
Hope Class I: Grand Cross (Gold)" from South African President
Nelson Mandela, which underscored the close ties between Malaysia
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was described as the "source of inspiration to the
developing world" through his eminent leadership in the United
Nations, Non-Aligned Movement and other international fora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
