<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Trade Deficit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- India's trade deficit widened by
almost one billion to 5.44 billion US dollars during 1996-97 due
to a sharp slowdown in export growth to 4 percent from the
previous year's 21 percent and an incremental petroleum oil import
bill of 2.5 billion US dollars, said the latest trade data
released by the Commerce Ministry here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Exports during 1996-97 were valued at 33.1 billion US dollars
reflecting only a modest growth over the 1995-96 performance of
31.8 billion. In March 1997, the last month of the 1996-97
financial year (April 1, 1996 to March 31, 1997), exports in fact
declined by 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports during 1996-97 were estimated at 38.5 billion US
dollars, a growth of 6 percent over imports worth 36.3 billion
during 1995-96. Oil imports during 1996-97 grew sharply by 34.3
percent to 9.61 billion from 7.15 billion US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
