<HEADLINE> Becker Wins, Stich Loses in German Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Boris Becker won his first ATP match
for nearly three months on Wednesday while compatriot Michael
Stich lost at the German Open in Hamburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Former world number one Becker has been suffering with a
long-term wrist injury but he overcame to beat 19-year-old fellow
German Nicolas Kiefer 7-5, 6-2 in the second round of the
clay-court tournament.
</P>
<P>
Becker, who surprisingly lost to Italian Renzo Furlan in the
first round at Monte Carlo two weeks ago, produced a reasonably
consistent performance in difficult conditions.
</P>
<P>
He had some alarms in the sixth game of the opening set when he
dropped serve but he broke back immediately.
</P>
<P>
After Becker had served out to love to take the first set he
looked much more in control, breaking Kiefer three times with just
one break back.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former Wimbledon champion and 16th seed Stich, who
recently announced he will retire in September, faded against
Czech Slava Dozedel and lost 7-6, 6-2 in windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
In the other matches of the day, Tommy Haas, ranked 114 place
below the ninth-rated Spaniard Carlos Moya, beat the Australian
Open finalist 6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Moya, seeded four, looked dispirited by the cold, windy
conditions and when he came back 2-5 to 4-5 in the first set he
had his momentum broken by a shower which stopped play for 20
minutes. He didn't find his form since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
