<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, US to Join Hands for Developing Edible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- India and the United States plan
to collaborate to develop genetically-engineered edible vaccines
against tropical diseases, an informed source said here today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first such venture between the two countries in a
frontier technology area having enormous commercial potential.
Edible vaccines are the latest concept in paediatric care where
instead of painful jabs, popular foods like chocolates are
converted into antibody carriers to target specific disease
causing virus and bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The current venture is part of an extended vaccine action
program between the two countries under which vaccines for
tropical diseases like Hepatitis and Rotaviral diarrhoea have been
developed. The edible virus program will work towards finding
antibodies for rabies, a disease estimated to claim over 1,000,000
lives every year. The research will target plants from which the
antibodies are to be derived.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of US and Indian biotechnology experts held here
during early March this year decided to enter this exciting area
of research. Under the broad agreement, specialized equipment and
technical help will come from the US while the work of finding
suitable antibodies from plants and cloning them into common
foodstuffs will be done by Indian scientists.
</P>
<P>
Edible vaccines are the object of intense research by major
pharmaceutical companies in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
