<HEADLINE> Think-Tank to Boost Australian Integration With Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- A high-powered think-tank and
research organization dedicated to fostering Australia's links
with Asia is to be set up in Sydney tonight.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard will launch the AustralAsia Center
of the Asia Society at a dinner with a statement of his
government's policy toward Asia, which is also considered a
rebuttal of the views of One Nation party founder Pauline Hanson.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said last week that the
Hanson policy of banning foreign investment and implementing a
racially discriminatory immigration policy would cripple Australia
in its attempts to engage in the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Chaired by Hugh Morgan of Western Mining, the center is
"entirely funded by the private sector and has the most
high-powered business support of any such group in Australia," The
Australian, one of the nation's leading newspapers, reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The paper described the move as a strong push made by the
Australian business community to intensify the nation's
integration with Asia.
</P>
<P>
The center's advisory council includes Don Argus of National
Australia Bank; Rod Eddington of Ansett, the national airline
company; Kerry Packer, a media tycoon and Australia's richest man;
Janet Holmes a Court, Australia's richest woman; and John Prescott
of BHP, the nation's leading steel producer.
</P>
<P>
From the academic world it includes Vice-Chancellor of
Melbourne University Alan Gilbert and Chancellor of Sydney
University Leonie Kramer.
</P>
<P>
Former Minister for Foreign Affairs Gareth Evans and Secretary
of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade Philip Flood are
among other luminaries on the advisory council.
</P>
<P>
The center has achieved a major coup in recruiting Richard
Woolcott, one of Australia's most distinguished diplomats and
Asianists, as its founding director.
</P>
<P>
Woolcott, former head of the Department of Foreign Affairs and
Trade, was Australia's ambassador to four Asian countries and
chairman of the Australia-Indonesia Institute.  
</P>
