<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Following two consecutive days of
sharp slide, the index of the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET)
sank to a five-and-half-year low on Wednesday, less than a point
above the level recorded on October 16, 1991.
</P>
<P>
The SET composite index on Wednesday lost 16.71 points, or 2.6
percent, to close at 626.57, falling through the key support level
of 630 points, with the lowest level on the day touching 618.66
points.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's plummet followed on the heels of Tuesday's decline
of 16.82 points, or 2.55 percent, the biggest single-day drop
since March 4.
</P>
<P>
At Wednesday's close, the benchmark index was 205 points, or
24.65 percent, down on its 1996's year-end close of 831.57 points.
</P>
<P>
The foreign-led selling over the last two days was caused by
rumors that the Thai economy, despite the rescue measures in
place, will not recover in the next two years, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The rumors have prompted foreign investors in particular to
liquidate their holdings and switch their focus to Asian economies
riding on the coattails of Wall Street's recent surge.
</P>
<P>
The index downturn was also part of the reaction to Deputy
Prime Minister and concurrently Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan's
prediction that Thailand would post a budget deficit in the
current fiscal year ending September.
</P>
<P>
He told a seminar on the local bond market that revenues in the
year so far have fallen well below targets and ruled out further
budget cuts before the end of the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Only two months ago, he forecast that the budget of this fiscal
year would post a surplus of 2 billion baht (80 million U.S.
dollars) after state spending cuts of 106 billion baht (4.24
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, investors dumped shares in expectation of poor
first-quarter corporate performance figures, which led to stocks
dropping across the board.
</P>
<P>
After all, the SET fell simply because investors still lacked
confidence in the market and funds were readjusting their
portfolio holdings, said Surachai Visitpongaree, an analyst with
ITF Finance and Securities PLC.
</P>
<P>
The stock markets were typically awash with rumors about
government reshuffles, baht depreciation or policy failures during
an economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, unofficial figures disclosed on Wednesday
indicated that the country's exports in the first quarter of 1997
registered a decline of 0.2 percent compared with the same period
of last year.
</P>
<P>
The slight decline compared with a 10-percent growth
authorities have forecast for this year. Last year the country's
exports were near zero growth.
</P>
<P>
With the export decline during the first three months of this
year, overall gross domestic product growth in the period would be
below 5 percent, against a forecast 6.8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
