<HEADLINE> Assets Confiscated From Italian Builder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Palermo Court confiscated
assets valued at over 1,000 billion lire (about 0.66 billion
U.S. dollars) from builder Vincenzo Piazza, who has been in jail
for the past three years for mafia association.
</P>
<P>
This was the largest single confiscation of assets. Among the
holdings confiscated were 2,500 rooms, 10 schools, 131 apartments,
122 warehouses, eight industrial sheds, thousands of hectares of
land in the provinces of Palermo, Ragusa and even Siena, where
Piazza owned farms. Many of the over one thousand apartments he
built are currently rented out to local governments and state
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Tax officials were able to ascertain that their total value and
volume were entirely incompatible with the possible income of the
builder and his family, who declared a taxable gross income of
1,857,000 lire (about 1,226 U.S. dollars) in 1989. Investigators
also determined that the funds available to Piazza could not "even
be justified by tax evasion".
</P>
<P>
A total of 20 companies had been impounded and grouped together
under two holding companies, Caravaggio and Leonardo Da Vinci,
registered in the names of Piazza's wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 thousand shares were also seized, equal to 8 percent
of the Sicilian savings bank's capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
