<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Public Enterprises to Be Given More Powers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
increased the powers of the boards of public enterprises to
sanction capital outlay in their enterprises without prior
government approval in a bid to boost their production and
development.
</P>
<P>
The powers have been revised with a view to giving greater
autonomy to public-sector enterprises and in pursuance of an
announcement made by Finance Minister P. Chidambaram in his budget
speech for 1997-98 in February this year, a government official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises with gross block of less than 1,000 million
rupees (28.17 million U.S. dollars) will now have the power to
decide on their own expenditure without prior government approval
of up to 100 million rupees (2.82 million dollars) against the
existing 50 million rupees (1.41 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The term "gross block" refers to fixed assets and capital work
in progress as shown in the last published balance sheet, the same
official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, those having gross block of between 1,000 million
and 2,000 million and 5,000 million rupees (28.17 million, 56.34
million and 140.85 million dollars) have the power to spend 1,000
million rupees without the prior approval of the government.
</P>
<P>
The enhanced delegated powers are subject to the condition that
the enterprise concerned should be profit-making. Another
condition is that the project is included in the approved
five-year and annual plans and outlays have been provided, the
same source added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
