<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO Predicts More Bananas Than Needed By 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) said today that under existing
production and trade conditions, banana supplies could exceed
demand by the end of the decade.
</P>
<P>
The FAO projects show global banana exports of 12.87 million
tons in 1999, facing an import demand of 12.22 million tons,
resulting in a 650,000 tons surplus.
</P>
<P>
However, the very recent entry of China into the importing
market could combine with emerging markets in Central and Eastern
Europe to absorb some of the projected surplus, said FAO.
</P>
<P>
The organization said bananas were the most important tropical
fruit in world trade, and of vital importance in the economic and
social well-being of most developing tropical countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
