<HEADLINE> Local Elections Postponed at Western Nepali Villages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's Election Commission has
indefinitely postponed local elections in over 40 villages of four
western districts where no nominations were filed, officials here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The commission decided Wednesday to direct local election
officers to issue notices of staying the elections, originally
scheduled on May 17, in these villages until further orders.
</P>
<P>
No single candidacy has been registered in 41 villages of west
Nepal's Rukum, Ropla, Jajarkot and Salyan districts as a leftist
guerrilla movement named "People's War" launched a boycott
campaign by spreading death threats among would-be candidates,
local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Candidates who filed their nominations Sunday in other villages
in the same hilly region, about 250 km west of Kathmandu, have
been reportedly withdrawing their names from the elections after
the guerrillas strengthened their threats by killing a candidate
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas have carried out a door-to-door campaign against
the polls, terrorizing the local people, a Rukum district officer
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nepali voters are scheduled to elect leaderships of nearly
2,000 villages in west Nepal on May 17 under the first phase of
the country's local elections.
</P>
<P>
The election's second phase will be conducted in central and
east Nepal on May 26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
