<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Ruling Party Reelects Top Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's ruling Awami (people's)
League (AL) reelected Sheikh Hasina and Zillur Rahman to the posts
of President and General Secretary of the party respectively on
the concluding day of its triennial National Council on Wednesday
</P>
<P>
They were unanimously declared elected Wednesday night by the
two-day 15th council of the party, the first such kind of meeting
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
With this election, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina became the
president for the fourth consecutive term of the 48-year-old
organization. The 50-year-old Hasina was made president of the AL
first in 1981 when she was in exile in India.
</P>
<P>
"I will try my best to perform my duties and serve the nation
by making the party more dynamic," Sheikh Hasina, whose party won
the last June general polls, told thousands of supporters after
she was reelected.
</P>
<P>
The AL's Council, which was earlier deferred four times due to
non-completion of conferences of its several district
organizational units, also declared a 13-member presidium with the
induction of two new leaders, Suranjit Sengupta and Abdul Jalil.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Sheikh Hasina announced a nine-point future
plan of action, including eradication of terrorism, checking
corruption and misuse of power, eradication of illiteracy and
alleviation of poverty.
</P>
<P>
She also vowed to build a Bangladesh free from poverty, hunger
and illiteracy by 2020 when the nation would celebrate the
centenary of the birth of its first president Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman, father of Sheikh Hasina.  
</P>
</TEXT>
