<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gold Market Varies Sharply in 1996: GFMS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Compared with the preceding years,
the gold market showed much more variation during 1996, due to the
weakness of investment and increased supply, Gold Fields Mineral
Services (GFMS) said.
</P>
<P>
In its annual publication, Gold 1997, GFMS said mine
production will reach 2,424 tons, increasing by 3.4 percent over the
2,346 tons of 1996, after having declined marginally in each of
the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
Total supply amounted to 3,490 tons compared with 3,629
tons in 1995, with non-official sector sales rising to 239
tons from 182 tons, and scrap increasing to 644 tons from
625 tons.
</P>
<P>
On the demand side, jewelery fabrication rose for the third
successive year, showing an increase of 40 tons, up 1.4 percent
to a new record level of 2,807 tons.
</P>
<P>
The use of gold in electronics, the second largest sector after
jewelery, rose for the fourth year in succession, with the
relatively modest increase of one percent.
</P>
<P>
The average prices in 1996, based on the average London (PM
fix), was 387.87 US dollars per ounce, one percent higher than
1995, with GFMS noting that with the sustained rise in the dollar
last year, the gold price in other currencies, particularly the
Rand, showed sustainable year-on-year increases.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the developments in early 1997 and the outlook
for the remainder of the year, GFMS chief executive Stuart Murray
said at the launch of Gold 1997: "The price weakness since the
last quarter of 1996 has been, to a large extent, the result of
poor sentiment, stemming above all from fears about the future
impact of the official sector on the gold market."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the evidence uncovered by GFMS was that
official sector in the gold market was not a "one-way street".
</P>
<P>
"Even more importantly, the physical market, which tended to
hold back in the final months of the year as the price was
falling, has now kicked in with a vengeance and is once again
providing a rather solid floor at the 340 US dollars level, in
spite of the continued strength of the dollar," Murray added.
</P>
<P>
On the question of the physical market gap, Murray noted that
"as in previous years, the current level of mine production and
scrap will continue to be insufficient to meet the demands for
fabrication and bar hoarding, and, the question is how this is
most likely to be filled in 1997." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0233 </DOCNO>
