<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan President Leaves for Central American-U.S. Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman
left here this morning for a regional summit where he will press
his U.S. counterpart to soften a new American immigration law.
</P>
<P>
Besides U.S. President Bill Clinton, Aleman will be joined at
the meeting in San Jose, Costa Rica, on Thursday by other leaders
of Central America and those of the Dominican Republic and Belize.
</P>
<P>
Following Aleman, Clinton left for San Jose tonight, to make
the first visit by a U.S. president to Central America since
former U.S. President George Bush traveled to Costa Rica in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure, Aleman told a press conference at the
airport of this Nicaraguan capital that the main topics of the
summit will be immigration and a hemispheric free trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan president, who was chosen to speak on behalf of
all Central American leaders, said he would ask Clinton to help
persuade U.S. Congress to repeal or change the new immigration law.
</P>
<P>
Effective April 1, the law makes it easier for deporting
illegal immigrants and bars immigrants from re-entering the United
States for up to 10 years after living there without authorization.
</P>
<P>
As many as 600,000 Central Americans now live in the United
States, and many of them are people who fled their countries to
escape civil wars that raged across the region in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Immigration is "the issue of greatest priority and importance"
for Nicaragua and El Salvador, the two countries of the region
most affected in the past decade by the civil wars, Aleman said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, all five Central American countries -- Costa Rica,
Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras and Nicaragua -- want to be
included in the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
The NAFTA went into effect on January 1, 1994, to group
together the economies of the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Aleman, who is accompanied by Foreign Minister Emilio Alvarez
Montalvan, said his government hopes the United States will grant
Central America the favorable treatment for NAFTA member nations.
</P>
<P>
Also on the agenda for the region's leaders at the coming
summit will be the signing of an "Open Skies" agreement between
Central American countries and the United States, he said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the president said, will ease restrictions on
commercial flights and lower air fares, and in turn will help
promote tourism and economic growth in Central America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
