<HEADLINE> Thailand's Exports in 1st Quarter Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exports in the first
quarter of this year were valued at 228 billion baht (9.12 billion
US dollars), a decline of 0.2 percent compared with the same
period of last year, according to a source at the Business
Economics Department.
</P>
<P>
The figures are not official but they indicate that reaching
the Thai government's growth target for the year could be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has forecast export value to reach 1,550
billion baht (62 billion dollars) this year, up 10 percent over
last year when growth was almost zero.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also registered a trade deficit of 66.9 billion baht
(2.6 billion dollars) in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Of the total exports in the first quarter, 73.7 percent were
industrial products, 14.4 were farm products and the rest were oil
and fuel.
</P>
<P>
The source was quoted today by local press as saying that with
the decline in export, overall gross domestic product growth in
the first quarter would be below 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Business Economics Department plans a meeting today to
review first-quarter exports. Representatives from the food,
textile and footwear industries will attend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
