<HEADLINE> Mexico Supports Set-up of Free Trade Area of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo emphasized here today that Mexico supports the proposal to
establish a huge free trade area of Americas at the beginning of
the 21th century.
</P>
<P>
In a conference with Mexican businessmen on "The Present and
Future of Mexico-U.S. Relations", Zedillo emphasized the role
played by the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
</P>
<P>
He said that thanks to NAFTA, Mexico became the United States'
third most important trade partner and trade has increased more
than 60 percent since the establishment of NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
Mexico is now exporting more goods to the United States than
China's Taiwan, Singapore and South Korea combined, Zedillo
explained.
</P>
<P>
Free trade is contributing to the building of a more intense
and orderly relations among North American countries and is
propitiating a more solid understanding among its governments,
said Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
He believed that Mexicans have to win the war against poverty
and inequality, clearly and definitely within the next century.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Mexicans want and will reach a market economy
that has a human face and heart and that will lend support to the
most needy in an effective way. 
</P>
