<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Scientists Identify Papaya Scourge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, MAY 7 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan researchers have
identified a new virus which reduces papaya yields by causing
many papaya blossoms to drop off, so preventing the growth of the
fruit.
</P>
<P>
The virus was detected and classified by the laboratory of
biotechnology and plant virology of the Microbiology Center of
Venezuela's Institute of Scientific Research.
</P>
<P>
Researchers also identified strains of the virus that were
infecting crops of yuca, zucchini, watermelon, pepper, garlic,
legumes and sisal.
</P>
<P>
Once crops were affected by the virus, the fruit would be
underweight, deformed, bitter in taste, and would ripen unevenly.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have developed diagnostic equipment for each of
the viral diseases and for determining which insects are
responsible for transmitting them, as well as the host plants.
</P>
<P>
In Venezuela, infections can also be seen in major
agricultural crops such as alfalfa, potatoes, beans, cucumber,
gourds, melons, bananas, cacti, citrus fruit and several
ornamental plants such as roses and lilies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
