<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nonferrous Industry Making Headway In World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
leads the country's nonferrous metallic industry and is making
efforts to compete more profitably in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Hunan's nonferrous metallic industry has met advanced world
standards for processing technology of stibium, lead, zinc, and
hard alloy. Products from the Zhuzhou Smeltery have been traded on
the London Metal Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The resource-rich province has 11 million tons of reserves of
10 major nonferrous metals, including copper, lead, and stibium.
Its reserves of wolfram, stibium, bismuth, and fluorite rank first
in China.
</P>
<P>
The Xikuangshan Mining Administration, known as the hometown of
stibium, leads the world in its annual production, while the
Zhuzhou Smeltery has become China's largest base for lead and zinc
export.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 kinds of products in the industry sell well in
over 30 countries, earning 200 million US dollars annually from
exports.
</P>
<P>
Industry insiders attribute the success to the large-scale
restructuring the province has carried out in the field. Some
enterprises were merged, nine of the 13 mining administrations
shifted to other production lines and development.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, mines have spent billion yuan on technological
upgrading. As a result, the province has increased its smelting
capacity by 69 percent, and its processing capacity by 111 percent.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology have also played a role in turning the
resource advantage into the economic advantage. More than 200
scientific and technological findings have been scored in the
nonferrous metallic industry over the past 10 years, and 85
percent of them have been applied to production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Accuses U.S. of Releasing Pests on Cuban Territary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Cuba has accused the United States
before the United Nations of releasing a plague of insects that is
affecting food crops on the western side of the island.
</P>
<P>
"Granma", the Cuban official newspaper said a duster airplane,
with the registration number N3093M of the U.S. State Department,
was sighted on October 21, 1996 when it was releasing substances
over Playa Giron, on western Cuba island, where insects were later
detected in their potato crops.
</P>
<P>
The insect, detected last December, is the thrip palmi karay,
of Asian origin, which attack all kinds of crops, according to
Cuba's central laboratory of plant sanitation.
</P>
<P>
In the denunciation presented to the United Nations last March,
the Cuban authorities described the incident as biological
aggression by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The operation carried out by the U.S. aircraft was observed by
the crew members of a Cuban aircraft that was flying over that
area.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban government said in its denunciation that the United
States released biological agents to deteriorate the food base on
this island in the Greater Antilles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
