<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Posts Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government posted a
6.6 billion pesos (252 million U.S. dollars) budget surplus in
April, a great improvement from a deficit recorded during the
first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press reports quoted officials from the Finance
Department as saying Wednesday that this is an indication that the
Philippine economy remains strong, despite the recent decline in
stock market prices.
</P>
<P>
For the first three months of this year, the government
registered a 648 million pesos (24.7 million dollars) deficit,
giving rise to concerns over the government's financial position.
</P>
<P>
But the reports said the government still failed to meet its
hefty surplus target of 16.3 billion pesos (620 million dollars)
for April it expected earlier.
</P>
<P>
For the entire year, the government estimates a budget surplus
of 13 billion pesos (494 million dollars). This projection is
already included in the macroeconomic targets under a supervision
program endorsed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
