<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Exports to EU Likely to Lose Tax Perks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Philippine export products to the
European Union (EU) are expected to lose the preferential
treatment by the year 2000 under the EU's new Generalized System
of Preference (GSP) scheme, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The EU is set to review the level of competitiveness of
products being exported to the EU from the GSP's beneficiary
countries, including Philippine products, by 2000, an EU official
was quoted as telling a press briefing here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting EU Counselor for Economic Affairs Pedro Martinez said
under the new GSP scheme, products that are found to be
competitive on the world market would graduate from the scheme.
</P>
<P>
These competitive products will then have to pay the standard
duty rate with a lower discount rate, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Products that are still uncompetitive would also pay the
standard duty rate but would be given a higher discount rate, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Discount rate could range from 10 percent to 60 percent,
according to Martinez. Under the old GSP scheme, all products from
beneficiary countries are given zero tariff rate.
</P>
<P>
Martinez explained that this new graduation mechanism was
designed to ensure a "system of fairness" in the GSP scheme.
</P>
<P>
He said Singapore used to share the same tariff privilege for
similar products lines with developing countries like Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Singapore and other countries like South Korea, Brazil, Brunei
and Chile had already been graduated from the GSP in February last
year.
</P>
<P>
The GSP is a unilateral trade program which grants preferential
treatment of tariffs to developing countries. The EU classified
the Philippines as a developing country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Ventures Embrace Displaced Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Workers laid-off from the public
sector are encouraged to seek job opportunities in private
enterprises in east China.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels are taking measures to give full play
to the role of private sector in the nation's reemployment
strategy. Zhejiang has granted preferential policies which
encourage the private sector to employ displaced workers. A
reemployment center has also debuted in Shanghai to help such
workers grab jobs in private ventures.
</P>
<P>
The private economy re-emerged in China in 1980s, providing
more convenience for people's life and creating more job
opportunities. But working in the private sector used to be
regarded as something far from an honor and was belittled by
workers in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
However, the conception shattered with the introduction of the
socialist market economy in recent years. And as the
cradle-to-grave welfare system disintegrated and social security
gradually took dominance, people are eyeing businesses as a
promising alternative to employment in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
In a job fair in April, more than 600 displaced workers were
reemployed by private ventures, Zhejiang. Private sector in
capital city of Hangzhou accepted 1,000 such employees.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the province plans to shuffle
another 200,000 displaced workers into the private ventures in the
upcoming three years and 30,000 to 50,000 displaced workers will
be taken into the private sector annually in Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
