<HEADLINE> NATO Head Opens Ukraine Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, May 7 (Xinhua) -- North Atlantic Treaty Organization
Secretary General Javier Solana arrived here today on a flying
visit to open a NATO Information and Documentary Center in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the center showed that relations between NATO
and Ukraine had solid grounds, Solana said after he landed for the
one-day vistit at Borispol International Airport in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
Later, Solana talked with Ukranian President Leonid Kuchma on
furthering ties between NATO and Ukraine and reducing conventional
forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The NATO Secretary General gave President Kuchma a draft
document on the special partnership between NATO and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Solana said both sides should try to have the document signed
at the NATO summit to be held in Madrid in July.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma told a press briefing after the talks that no problems
existed in relations between Ukraine and NATO, and development of
the Ukraine-NATO ties had a bright future.
</P>
<P>
Solana also held talks today with Ukranian Foreign Minister
Gennady Udovenko on the reduction of conventional forces in Europe
and the steps to be taken by Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko told reporters that both sides had reached a mutual
understanding on the issue.
</P>
<P>
However, when meeting with Ukraine's Chairman of the Supreme
Soviet (Parliament), Alexander Moroz, Solana was told that 187
Ukranian parliamentary members, accounting for 42 percent of all
lawmakers, had today formed a non-governmental organization (NGO)
called Ukraine Outside NATO.
</P>
<P>
Members of the NGO, mostly from the Communist Party, the
Socialist Party and the Peasants' Party, aim to stop NATO's
eastward expansion and to prevent Ukraine from joining the
military alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
