<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kasparov Draws with Deep Blue Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- World champion Garry Kasparov
drew with Deep Blue computer again in the fourth game of the
six-game series at New York, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
After five hours and the computer's 56th move, Kasparov
offered the draw while the computer accepted immediately. It was
the second draw between the 34-year-old Russian world champion
and Deep Blue supercomputer.
</P>
<P>
After the first four games, Kasporov and Deep Blue each had
two points from one win, two draws and one loss.
</P>
<P>
The computer played white on Wednesday. Kasparov played
cautiously at the outset to avoid engagements that would allow
the computer to take advantage of its superior calculating skills.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov sacrificed a pawn on his 20th move to make room to
maneuver his queen, rooks and knights. Deep Blue advanced pawns
around its king, creating weaknesses in the computer's position.
</P>
<P>
Kasparov then took advantages with his rooks and recaptured a
pawn from Deep Blue on his 35th move.
</P>
<P>
Around the 45th move, the supercomputer tried to obtain a draw
by repeating moves, but Kasparov ignored the offer, choosing to
play on.
</P>
<P>
But after 11 moves, Kasparov agreed that the deadlock was
permanent and the game came to an end.
</P>
<P>
Game 5 and 6 of the series are to be played on Saturday and
Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Urges Reforms of Employment System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- China is facing a severe
unemployment problem and, possibly, it will have to face this
problem until the beginning of the next century, an economist
warned.
</P>
<P>
This is because the growth of urban jobs can hardly keep pace
with the influx of rural labourers and the growing urban
population, today's "China Daily" quoted Zhou Qiren, a professor
at the China Center for Economic Research of Beijing University,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed, during the 1985-94 period, China's urban
population grew at an annual rate of 10.23 million. The figure
would reach 15.23 million if rural labourers who moved to work in
cities were included.
</P>
<P>
This growing urban population has proven too large for
state-owned urban enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The only way to deal with urban unemployment is to carry out
the employment and welfare reform in state-owned sectors to form a
highly competitive labour market, Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Such reforms might lower salary and welfare standards that are
artificially high when compared to low bank rates and low
productivity.
</P>
<P>
Reduced salaries that reflect the true productivity of
state-owned enterprises will discourage many rural labourers from
entering cities, put the growth of the national economy back on a
sound track and prevent urbanization from developing too fast.
</P>
<P>
Zhou suggests that while resolutely enaging in such reform
measures, China should also take up a series of complementary
procedures:
</P>
<P>
First, the government should let the bank rate be decided by
the market to ensure a more efficient allocation of
resources. Capital and labour must at last reflect the realities
of surplus labour and insufficient capital.
</P>
<P>
Second, authorities should try to let enterprises of different
ownerships compete on an equal footing and refrain from prejudice
against non-state-owned businesses when giving bank loans.
</P>
<P>
Third, authorities should adjust taxes imposed on township
enterprises so they can create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the government should create a more favourable
environment and policies for the export of labour and
labour-intensive products.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, central authorities should let local governments deal
with laid-off workers, other unemployed people and job retraining
according to their own conditions.
</P>
<P>
China should proceed with reforms in urban state-owned sectors
regardless of unemployment pressure. Only with the reforms can
China find a way to use labour resources more effectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Pledges Compliance on Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has
pledged that Russia will abide by the international treaty banning
chemical arms.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made in a letter to United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan. Russia is among the signatories of the
Chemical Weapons Convention, which came into effect on April 29,
but the Russian parliament has failed to ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin wrote that the main obstacle in the way to ratifying
the treaty was the problem of money needed to destroy the
country's chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The letter was made public today by the Russian President's
Press Office.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that if the international community could give
Russia vigorous help, Russia would be able to accelerate its
process of destroying chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Though the treaty had not been ratified by the Russian
parliament, Russia would, as always, fulfil its obligations
stipulated by the treaty, the letter said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
