<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Ministerial Meeting Opens in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of labor ministers from
Latin American countries opened here today to discuss labor
matters facing the region with the participation of Director
General of the International Labor Organization (ILO) Michel
Hansenne.
</P>
<P>
Chaired by Costa Rican Labor Minister Farid Ayales, the two-day
gathering will discuss the role of the labor ministry under the
new economic conditions, and problems that have a direct effect on
working conditions, such as economic globalization and migration.
</P>
<P>
Ayales appealed for improvement of the workers' working
conditions, saying that in spite of different development
characteristics of each nation, workers' fundamental rights should
be respected by all countries.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Hansenne told participants that the ILO is
promoting three initiatives for handling poverty, which swells the
team of workers.
</P>
<P>
He noted the first was to link development policies with market
access, saying international financial organizations such as the
international Monetary fund (IMF) and the World Bank should
coordinate their policies with the ILO.
</P>
<P>
The second initiative is to improve control mechanisms so that
ILO member nations will respect the fundamental dispositions of
the international conventions on labor matters.
</P>
<P>
Finally, he proposed an improvement in policies concerning
employment.
</P>
<P>
Labor ministers from Uruguay, the Dominican Republic, Panama,
El Salvador and Belize as well as public officials from other
countries of the region attended the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
