<HEADLINE> China's Sichuan Sees Quarterly Tax Revenue Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan Province
collected 2.77 billion yuan (about 330 million US dollars) in
industrial and commercial taxes in the first quarter of this year,
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 26.6 percent increase from the same
period a year ago, according to the Provincial Tax Bureau.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that the revenue of the value-added
tax and income tax, two major taxes under China's new tax regime
introduced in 1994, was 2.58 billion yuan in the January-March
period, a rise of 5.2 percent over same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
An official of the bureau said that the increase in the tax
revenue was due largely to enhanced collection, especially of
delayed taxes.
</P>
<P>
An effective mechanism for clearing delayed taxes was
established across the province at the beginning of this year,
according to the official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
