<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (69-70) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (69-70) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: How many Hong Kong banks issue currency today? Will
they continue to do so after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: For various historical reasons, Hong Kong does not have
a central bank. Its currency is issued by commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
For a very long period of time, the Hong Kong dollar has been
issued by the Shanghai and Hong Kong Banking Corporation and the
Standard Chartered Bank. On May 1, 1994, the Hong Kong Bank of
China joined in the issue of the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
At present three banks in Hong Kong issue currency. They are
the Shanghai and Hong Kong Banking Corporation, the Standard
Chartered Bank and the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Banks issuing the Hong Kong dollar must obtain interest-free
certificates of liabilities from the foreign exchange fund against
100 percent assets in US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Such certificates will serve as the basis of eligibility for
currency issues. The foreign exchange fund will be managed by the
Hong Kong Financial Commission to ensure the stability of the
Hong Kong dollar and Hong Kong's monetary system.
</P>
<P>
Article 111 of the Basic Law stipulates, "The authority to
issue Hong Kong currency shall be vested in the Government of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. The issue of Hong Kong
currency must be backed by a 100 percent reserve fund. The system
regarding the issue of Hong Kong currency and the reserve fund
system shall be prescribed by law. The Government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region may authorize designated banks to
issue or continue to issue Hong Kong currency under statutory
authority, after satisfying itself that any issue of currency will
be soundly based and that the arrangements for such issue are
consistent with the object of maintaining the stability of the
currency."
</P>
<P>
Its thus quite obvious that the system regarding the issue of
Hong Kong currency and the reserve fund system will remain
unchanged, and that the three existing currency-issuing banks will
continue to issue Hong Kong dollars in accordance with statutory
provisions.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will there be any restrictions on the flow of capital
within, into and out of Hong Kong after 1997? Will the business
of foreign-funded enterprises be taken over by mainland-funded
enterprises?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Article 112 of the Basic Law stipulates, "No foreign
exchange control policies shall be applied in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region. The Government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall protect the free flow of
capital within, into and out of the Region."
</P>
<P>
Article 115 of the law stipulates, "The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region shall pursue the policy of free trade and
safeguard the free movement of goods, intangible assets and
capital."
</P>
<P>
This means that doing business in Hong Kong after 1997 will
continue to be freer and more convenient than in other countries
and regions, with businesses there enjoying low tax rates and high
returns on their investment and at the same time being able to
freely transfer their capital and profits.
</P>
<P>
It will be impossible for mainland-funded enterprises to take
over the business of foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Article 105 of the Basic Law stipulates, "The ownership of
enterprises and the investments from outside the Region shall be
protected by law."
</P>
<P>
Article 118 of the law stipulates, "The Government of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region shall provide an economic and
legal environment for encouraging investments, technological
progress and the development of new industries."
</P>
<P>
After 1997, mainland-funded enterprises will cooperate with,
and compete fairly against, businesses funded by capital from
various countries and those funded by local Chinese capital under
rules as prescribed by the Basic Law and laws of the Hong Kong
SAR. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Announces 2.5 Billion US Dollar Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 8 (Xinhua) -- leases of three major airports in
Australia have been awarded to private consortiums at the price of
2.5 billion US dollars, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Awarding of the renewable 50-year leases, including the
airports of Melbourne, Brisbane and Perth, was announced Wednesday
by Minister for Finance John Fahey and Minister for Transport and
Regional Development John sharp.
</P>
<P>
A group dominated by the life insurance giant AMP and a British
company, BAA, will pay the federal government 1.307 billion
Australian dollars (1.01 billion US dollars) for Melbourne
Airport, the Melbourne-based newspaper The Age reported.
</P>
<P>
The group expected to earn an "internal rate of return" on the
airport of 14 percent before tax, officials of the new owner,
Australian Pacific Airports, was quoted by the newspaper as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Brisbane Airport was valued at 1.387 billion Australian
dollars (1.07 billion US dollars) and Dutch interests will play a
lead role at the airport, the Canberra Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The payments for the leases are higher than originally
envisaged, increasing optimism for the value of the Sydney Airport
lease, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The airport leasing arrangements, initiated by the former
Keating Labor government, will have the effect of substantially
restoring the federal government's budget fortunes, easing the
need for further major expenditure cuts.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said the successful bidders were contractually
committed to long-term development obligations, including
substantial investment in core airport infrastructure totaling
more than 500 million Australian dollars (389 million US dollars)
during the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The successful bidders had also agreed to comply with the
government's post-privatization pricing regime, said the
ministers.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would result in real reductions in aeronautical
charges ranging from 18.5 percent in Melbourne, 20.6 percent in
Brisbane and 24.6 percent for Perth over the next five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
