<HEADLINE> Mobile Eye Clinic Set Up in East Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 8 (Xinhua) -- China's first ophthalmic mobile
clinic has gone into operation in this capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The clinic, with medical instruments and surgical equipment
installed in a special car, was set up with about 100,000 US
dollars of donations from different social sectors in the province.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the famous Orbis airborne hospital, the automobile
needs less investment and is suitable for use in remote
mountainous areas, according to Professor Yao Ke with the No. 2
Hospital attached to Zhejiang Medical University.
</P>
<P>
Yao, who initiated the hospital, said that there are some
266,000 blind people in Zhejiang, of which 60 percent are victims
of cataracts or corneal diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these patients live in remote mountainous areas, and
many of them can be treated and even cured if they have access to
proper medical treatment," said the professor.
</P>
<P>
The clinic will soon travel to Lishui in southwest Zhejiang, to
provide free consultation and treatment to local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
