<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Direct Coal Liquefaction Plant in Sight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 8 (Xinhua) -- China may build the world's first
facility to directly convert coal into clean, quality fuel oil in
an effort to allay fears over pollution and the eventual depletion
of crude oil, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The consideration for one such facility was encouraged
yesterday in Beijing by China's Ministry of the Coal Industry and
Germany's State of North Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
Minister Wang Senhao and the German State's Economic Minister
Wolfgang Clement exchanged documents for a co-operative
feasibility study on a strategic direct coal liquefaction
demonstration plant.
</P>
<P>
According to the documents, the China Coal Research Institute
and the German firm of RUR and the German institute of DMT will
spend two years preparing the feasibility study.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the study will lead to the construction of the
world's first direct coal liquefaction into fuel oil plant in
China's southwestern province of Yunnan, which is rich in coal
reserves suitable for liquefaction.
</P>
<P>
The liquefaction plant will be operational within four
years. It will process 1.7 million tons of brown coal
annually. Output will include 600,000 tons of diesel fuel and
gasoline. The quality will also be good enough to serve as fuel
for aircraft, Zhu Deren, president of the China Coal Research
Institute, said.
</P>
<P>
A mine will be operated in Yunnan capable of excavating 3
million tons of brown coal a year to serve the plant.
</P>
<P>
The technology and experience China has accumulated over the
past 17 years show that the liquefied coal fuels may cost less
than fuels refined from crude oil, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
However, solutions to problems concerning industrial production
and market prospects depend on the feasibility study.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, China is discussing co-operative possibilities
with governments and enterprises of the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said China has some 115 billion tons of coal reserves and
diverse requirements for clean coal technology and development,
and welcomes foreign governments and enterprises to try other
kinds of technologies with kinds of different coal.
</P>
<P>
In China, crude oil will only last for a couple of decades,
while the reserves of coal ensures exploitation for at least 100
years. Imports of crude oil are expected to increase to 40 to 50
million tons by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Globally speaking, commercial utility of coal in a clean way
would bring about a revolutionary change in mankind's energy
consumption, Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
