<HEADLINE> Australian Takes Second Stage in Dunkirk Cycling Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Robbie McEwen of Australia took the
second state of the Dunkirk Four Days cycling race at
Montigny-en-Gohelle, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
McEwen won the sprint to the line ahead of Djamolidin
Abdujaparov of Uzbekistan to win the 184-kilometer second stage.
</P>
<P>
Abdujaparov finished second in the stage, followed by Jaan
Kirsipuu of Estonia in the third place.
</P>
<P>
Wilfried Peeters of Belgium retained the overall leader's pink
jersey.
</P>
<P>
Arturas Kasputis of Lithuania broke away alone early on. But
the chasing group caught up with him a few kilometers from the
finish line and McEwen out-sprint his opponents in the final
sprint.
</P>
<P>
The third stage of 93.2 kilometers from Roost-Warendin to
Saint-Quentin will be held on Thursday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
