<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Credit Increase Slows Down in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The outstanding consumer credit
in the U.S. increased at a 2 percent seasonally adjusted annual
rate in March, the slowest since last September, the U.S. Federal
Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate followed an increase of annual rate of 6.7
percent in February and 10.3 percent in January. It was the lowest
monthly increase since a revised 0.8 percent increase rate in
September of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said that credit card debt increased by 1.5 billion
dollars in March, compared with a revised gain of 5 billion in the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money owed on automobile loans shrank by 1.1
billion dollars after rising 300 million in February.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding balances on loans used for education, vacations or
boat and trailer purchases increased by 1.6 billion following an
increase of 1.5 billion in February.
</P>
<P>
At the year-on-year level, U.S. consumer credit was up by 6.9
percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Total outstanding consumer credit in the U.S. reached 1212.2
billion dollars in March, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, consumer confidence and credit levels in the U.S.
have remained high for the last several months, due in part to
relatively low interest rates and steady economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks sank sharply today,
with investors securing more profits from the market's dramatic
rebound.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average, which closed at record highs
on Monday and Tuesday, gave back 139.67 points at 7,085.65. It
gained nearly 500 points from the previous seven sessions.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled
497.58 million shares as against 601.30 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 12.14 to 815.62, and
the NYSE composite index fell 5.82 to 424.95.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 5.38 to 1,322.92, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 0.01 to 570.50.
</P>
<P>
The market was also weighed down by another weak day in the
bond market, where long-term interest rates have been creeping
back toward worrisome levels.
</P>
<P>
The bond market pulled back today by more signals from the
Federal Reserve that inflation remains a threat.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported today that U.S. productivity
increased at a 2 percent annual rate in the first quarter, the
best in more than three years, but the improvement was not as
strong as some had hoped. Improving productivity enables companies
to raise wages without raising prices because workers are
producing more with the same amount of work.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices slipped today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
rose to 6.96 percent from late Tuesday's 6.89 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the long-bond yield plunged below 7 percent for the
first time in about a month which gave the stock market a boost.
</P>
<P>
Although the Fed is widely expected to raise rates again at a
May 20 policy meeting, investors fear that the central bank may
raise rates repeatedly, slowing consumer spending and company
profits.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
