<HEADLINE> US Local Phone Giant to Acquire Internet Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The GTE Corporation, the largest
local telephone company in the United States said Tuesday that it
had agreed to pay 616 million U.S. dollars in cash to acquire the
BBN Corporation, one of the Nation's biggest Internet service
companies.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at becoming a major operator of corporate
data networks which will then be able to open a new round of
fierce competition against the big long-distance companies
including the AT&AMP;T Corporation, the New York Times commented in a
report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are undergoing very dramatic, fundamental change in our
industry. We are becoming a nation-wide provider of
telecommunications services--voice, data and video," Charles R.
Lee, GTE's chairman, was quoted as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T is the leader in running national corporate networks, with
about 60 percent of a 12 billion U.S. dollar market, followed by
the MCI Communications Corporation, the Sprint Corporation and
Worldcom Inc.
</P>
<P>
"Together we are an almost perfect strategic fit-- our
technology and their resources," George H. Conrads, BBN's
chairman, said of the proposed merger with GTE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
