<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook, Kinkel Warn Against Further Construction of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Both British and German foreign
ministers warned Israel today against the further construction of
the Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem, saying that it would
destroy the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is quite clear that the Har Homa settlement is
both wrong in principle and deeply damaging the peace process,"
said the new British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook at a news
conference after talks with German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
in Bonn Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"We'll not be able to keep the peace process alive if there is
not progress in the peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cook also made clear that Britain would be anxious to use its
voice to make sure that both parties of the peace process do not
do any thing that is going to make it more difficult for the other
part to reach agreement within the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel meanwhile assured Germany's full support of the European
policy on the issue, saying "we too believe the establishment of
the settlement in east Jerusalem is not acceptable.... and agree
that peace process in Middle East is a process to which there is
no alternative."
</P>
<P>
At their talks Wednesday, Cook also assured Kinkel that Britain
would "show full solidarity" with Germany concerning its relations
with Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain would not send its ambassador back to
Teheran in advance of any decision to return an ambassador there
from Germany.
</P>
<P>
Germany's ambassador was recalled from Teheran after a German
court ruling that Iran's leaders were responsible for the 1992
killings in Berlin of three exiled dissidents and their
translator. Iran made clear recently that it would not welcome the
return of Germany's ambassador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
