<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Expansion for Habitat's Governing Body </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The 58-member U.N. Commission on
Human Settlements will not include non-governmental groups or
local authorities, said a resolution passed by the commission's
16th session ending today.
</P>
<P>
However, the resolution called for highlighting the role of
these groups and the spirit of partnership in the effective
implementation of the Habitat Agenda aimed at offering adequate
shelters to people all over the world.
</P>
<P>
It asked the governments to consider to admit representatives
of non-government groups, local authorities, private sector and
research organizations into their delegations to future sessions
of the commission.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the governing body of the U.N. Center for
Human Settlements (Habitat), approved a total of 27 resolutions
at the end of the biennial session starting on April 28.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions focused on how to strengthen the Habitat
especially by improving the management, the setting-up of Habitat
regional offices in Japan, Jordan and other countries, and so on.
</P>
<P>
During the session, as many as 23 countries pledged more
financial support to the work of the Habitat in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
