<HEADLINE> Dollar Weakens on Japan Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended most lower
Wednesday here and briefly dipped below 125 yen for the first time
in a month, hurt by Japan's growing trade surplus and a Japanese
news report of central-bank preparations to sell dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar surged to a nearly seven-week high against the
British pound after the new Foreign Secretary Robin Cook suggested
the country might participate in Europe's single currency plan.
</P>
<P>
The dollar traded as low as 124.85 yen in Asian dealings, the
lowest level since early April, before recouping a bit to settled
at 125.13 yen in New York, down from 125.40 Tuesday. The dollar
traded at 1.7212 marks, down from 1.7228. The pound cost 1.6113
U.S. dollars, down from 1.6337 U.S. dollars, the lowest since
March 21.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's lows came after Japanese trade data were released
showing that Japan posted a 2.82 billion U.S. dollars trade
surplus in the first 20 days of April, compared with a 472 million
U.S. dollars deficit in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The trade report reinforced fears that the United States and
Japan would take action to cap the dollar's growing value against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
The fears were intensified when the Kyodo news service of Japan
quoted an unidentified monetary source as saying the Group of
Seven countries were preparing to sell dollars to prevent the yen
from weakening further.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday:
1.4610 Swiss francs, down from 1.4619; 5.7965 French francs, down
from 5.8095; 1,701.25 Italian lira, down from 1,705.00; 1.3820
Canadian dollars, up from 1.3782. 
</P>
</TEXT>
