<HEADLINE> Rinderpest Epidemic Breaks out In Northern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Rinderpest epidemic has
broken out in northern Tanzania, which constitutes a serious
threat to both livestock and wildlife, the national news agency
SHIHATA reported today.
</P>
<P>
Rinderpest, a highly contagious killer disease of domestic and
wild animals, was detected in northern Tanzania since early
January this year, and it is feared that it might have already
spread to other areas due to long distance movements of livestock
which prevailed during the recent drought.
</P>
<P>
Rinderpest epidemic was recognized in Kenya last October and
by January, 1997 had spread across the border into northern
Tanzania, the SHIHATA said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) has
granted Tanzania 430,144 US Dollars for rapid containment and
elimination of Rinderpest epidemic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
