<HEADLINE> Lebanon Warns Against Close Ties Between Turkey, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz warned here today against close ties between Turkey and
Israel, noting that Lebanon was "looking with worry" at the
growing relationship between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz made the remarks following a reportedly planned joint
maneuvers by Israeli, Turkish and U.S. forces in the
Mediterranean, the state-run Lebanese National News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey has common history and interests in various fields
with the Arab, and it should not give a depth to its relationship
with Israel which makes some to interpret or extract that Turkey
was part of an aggression against Arab states," Boueiz was quoted
as saying by the agency.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign minister said he did not see a
crystallization of a tripartite alliance formed by Turkey, Israel
and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Until this moment, the U.S. and Turkey have only said that
the thing is revolving round the technical cooperation and
military cooperation, actually outside a political-military
alliance," the Lebanese official said.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking with worry at these developments, especially
after we heard informations in the last hours on a participation
of the U.S. in the future military maneuvers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot separate this thing from a political-military
encirclement or a political-military alliance which is aimed to
blockade positions of some Arab states," the foreign minister
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Several Arab states have been upset by a report that
General Cevik Bir, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Turkish
military, flew to Israel Sunday to help plan joint maneuvers by
Israeli, Turkish and U.S. forces in the Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
