<HEADLINE> Russian, Spanish Diplomats on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia hopes that Spain will take
into account Russia's position on NATO's eastward expansion plan
during the discussion of these issues in the Alliance, Russian
Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with Spanish Foreign
Minister Abel Matutes y Juan, Ivanov noted that Russia outlined
its vision of the future European security system.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish foreign minister was accompanying King Juan Carlos
I of Spain on a three-day state visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Though Russia and Spain have different opinions on NATO
eastward enlargement, Ivanov said, they agreed that it is
necessary to alleviate, as much as possible, the consequences of
the expansion.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two sides "have agreed to actively cooperate
in order to work out a European security charter for the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
Touching today's talks between Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana in Luxembourg,
Ivanov said the "responsible character" of the current stage of
work on the document between Russia and NATO and the "delicate
nature" of the issues were discussed.
</P>
<P>
Described the talks as "very hard," he said, "It would be
premature to make any forecasts." Primekov and Solana will
continue their talks in Moscow next week, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish foreign minister, on his part, said that Russia's
security is an "imperative factor" for the security of his country
and its NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Russia should feel at ease within the framework of
the agreements to be concluded in accordance with such a European
security scheme as may be adopted by NATO."
</P>
<P>
Abel Matutes y Juan stressed that NATO expansion is not aimed
against Russia and that Spain shares some of Moscow's concerns
over NATO's enlargement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
