<HEADLINE> Turkey Willing to Dialog With Greece on Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is willing to enter into any
kind of dialog with neighboring Greece in a bid to solve bilateral
disputes, a Turkish official said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Atacanli told
reporters here that the first meeting of a joint committee
designed to define Turkey-Greece problems will be held in mid-May
in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands, the current European Union rotary president,
proposed to establish the committee and a four-person group is
scheduled to submit its report on this in June.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli pointed out that the report would not be binding on
the governments, but that they would evaluate the report and use
it to decide on possible future studies and actions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry Undersecretary Onur Oymen, who met his Greek
counterpart Yorgo Papandreau in Strasbourg late Tuesday, said
improving Turkey-Greece relations needed a step-by-step approach
and both sides should be patient.
</P>
<P>
He added that he and his Greek counterpart shared the belief
that with goodwill from both sides it would be possible to achieve
positive results.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, have long been at odds
over a number of issues including the limits of air space,
mineral rights below the Aegean Sea as well as the Cyprus
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
