<HEADLINE> Newspaper: Top US Official May Spy for Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The FBI is investigating whether
a senior U.S. government official has been providing sensitive
information to Israel, the Washington Post said today.
</P>
<P>
The FBI launched the investigation in January after the
National Security Agency intercepted a secure communication
between a senior Israeli intelligence officer in Washington and a
superior in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
In the intercepted conversation, the Tel Aviv superior asked
the Washington-based agent to use someone code-named "Mega" to
obtain a secret letter from then Secretary of State Warren
Christopher to Palestinian leader Yassir Arafat on Israeli troop
withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the Washington-based officer
rejected this suggestion, saying, "This is not something we use
Mega for."
</P>
<P>
U.S. government officials said that the context of the
conversation led them to believe that Mega may be someone in the
U.S. government who has provided information to the Israelis in
the past.
</P>
<P>
Israel denied that it has been using a highly-placed U.S.
government source for confidential information and its ambassador
to Washington Eliahu Ben Elissar said the allegation must
originate with "an evil-intentioned source."
</P>
<P>
"I deny it as strongly as one can deny anything," Elissar said.
"I simply think this allegation is ridiculous. Of course, I cannot
guarantee for everybody, but if anybody in this embassy had this
conversation or such a thought, he can be considered an utter
fool, a fool," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
