<HEADLINE> UAE Considers Measures Against Ships Violating UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The government of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) is considering measures against ships violating the
U.N. trade sanctions on Iraq, the UAE's official Wam news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Sheikh Hamdan bin Zayed
al-Nahyan discussed with some UAE senior officials this afternoon
the "more and more" violations by some ships hanging UAE flags
against the U.N.-imposed sanctions, Wam said.
</P>
<P>
The agency gave no details of the measures and violations. But
informed sources here said that the violations were likely made by
some ships delivering food, clothes and other aid items from
Dubai, one of the seven emirate of the UAE, to Iraq in accordance
with the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food deal signed in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
On their way back to the UAE, these ships were loaded with
Iraqi goods such as date palms. Such move is banned by the
U.N. trade sanctions against Iraq imposed on it after Iraq invaded
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollar
worth of oil over a six month period for purchasing food and
medicines for its people who have been suffering under the
U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
