<HEADLINE> British Parliament Assembles After Labor Wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Newly-elected members of the British
parliament swore in today, with Betty Boothroyd re-elected speaker
of the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
This was the first sitting of parliament since the May 1
election when Tony Blair's Labor Party stormed into power with an
overall majority of 179.
</P>
<P>
The political change which ended 18 years of Conservative rule
brought some 260 new faces into the 659-member House, including a
record number of 120 women.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on the opening day of the new parliament, Prime
Minister Tony Blair told the 418-strong contingent of Labor
parliament members, "We have the chance to do something quite
special, possibly even quite spectacular, for the future of our
country."
</P>
<P>
But he warned that voters who had turned to Labor in their
millions could just as easily eject the party in five years' time
if they felt their trust had been betrayed.
</P>
<P>
Pledging to carry out Labor's promises, Blair said that his
party was already beginning to make a difference within days of
taking office, improving relations with the European Union and
handing over control of interest rates to the nation's central
bank. 
</P>
