<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Promises to Be Constructive Instead of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Signaling the end of an old era,
visiting Britain's new Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said here
today that the new Labour government in London want to make the
country a leading player within the European Union (EU) which will
be constructive instead of obstructive in future European
construction.
</P>
<P>
"It's our intention that Britain should from now on be one of
those leading members of Europe, not a country on the sideline,
seeking to be obstructive to the direction of Europe. We want to
be helping to shape the direction of Europe," said Cook at a news
conference after talks with his German counterpart Klaus Kinkel
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
It was the first foreign visit by Cook since he took office
last week. Before coming to Bonn, Cook had also paid a visit to
Paris.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters in Bonn that his visit to Paris and Bonn
itself was a signal that Britain wanted to show that it was taking
Europe seriously and wished to be taken seriously within Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We're determined to draw a line under the sterile and negative
confrontation of the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first concrete result of Cook's first foreign visit was a
joint statement by Britain, France and Germany Wednesday, in which
the three countries promised to intensify their cooperation in the
field of arms control and disarmament, and to seek, in particular,
the early conclusion of a global agreement to ban anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
Cook said the statement had demonstrated how the three biggest
EU countries can reach agreement and make an impact on foreign and
European policy "by working together rather than treating each
other as negotiating opponents".
</P>
<P>
On his government's future European program, Cook said first of
all, London would make common efforts with other EU countries to
bring the ongoing Inter-Governmental Conference (IGC) on EU
reforms to an successful end at the June summit of the EU in
Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Although he added that there would be some difficult areas
which affect different national interests, Cook expressed the
confidence that an overall package that is good for all would be
reached in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
Cook also said that once Britain took over EU presidency in the
first half of 1998, it would make efforts to speed up the
negotiations on EU enlargement to eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
London would also make sure that the EU would complete the
single European market by removing the remaining obstacles to the
free movement of goods and services, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the planned January 1, 1999 launching of the single European
currency -- the Euro, Cook reiterated that Britain was "unlikely"
to make the first wave to join the club.
</P>
<P>
"It is for Germany and other countries of Europe to decide
whether it is right for them to proceed with the Euro on that
timetable," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
But "once it was so decided, Britain is not going to put any
obstacle in the way of those who wish to proceed," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970508.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt to Launch Clean-up Campaign to Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has embarked on a three-year
campaign to keep the Great Pyramids in Giza here from harm's way,
an Egyptian official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The government has recently approved a plan to develop the Giza
plateau south of Cairo aimed at keeping tourist buses, cars and
animals as far away as possible from the area, Zahi Hawass,
director of the Pyramid Antiquities Compound, told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
A 10-kilometer "tourist ring road," including parking places, a
cultural and recreational center and a new station for camels,
horses and horse carts, will be built just south of the Pyramids,
he said.
</P>
<P>
As part of a clean-up campaign, the shacks and slum buildings
near the Pyramids will be demolished and villagers will be settled
elsewhere, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the tradition of picnicking around Pyramids which
many Egyptians have followed over thousands of years, will be
changed if not completely disrupted, according to Hawass.
</P>
<P>
"Soon we will stop people from feasting at sites of Pyramids
and set a special picnicking area in the desert," he said.
</P>
<P>
All these practices are part of a three-year plan of the
Egyptian government to clean up the Pyramids, one of the surviving
Seven Wonders of the world.
</P>
<P>
Defending the somewhat radical plans, Hawass, a renowned
Egyptologist, said "We are not working for one day or tomorrow,
but for future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that without proper conservation, 15 percent of the
archeological sites in the Nile Delta he visited two years ago are
simply gone now.
</P>
<P>
Before it is too late, Hawass said, much more should be done for
the benefit of the Pyramids, like closing the smallest Pyramid for
six months due to the humidity caused by tourists.
</P>
<P>
There are now 105 pyramids all over Egypt, where over 5,000
years of history have bred a wealth of pharaonic, Roman and
Islamic relics.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 4,200 tombs have been recovered in Giza alone, only
19 of which are open to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
