<HEADLINE> Algeria Asks France to Return Archives of Colonial Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Algeria today asked France to return
some 200,000 files of archives of its colonial times dating from
1830 to 1962, as well as some archives of the Ottoman period
before French occupation.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Abdelkrim Badjadja, the
director of the Center of Archives of Algeria, as saying that
Algeria has only got back 60 files of its colonial time archives
since 1962.
</P>
<P>
He said that some Algerian archives dating from the times of
Ottoman Turkish rule are now kept in Aix-en-Provence, southern
France.
</P>
<P>
AFP said that the debate on the return of the archives was
triggered by the commemoration of anniversary of the massacres of
May 8, 1945, in which French troops brutally suppressed a protest
by Algerians in eastern Algeria.
</P>
<P>
According to Algerian historians, about 45,000 people were
killed in the massacres. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
