<HEADLINE> Turkey Firmly Supports Azerbaijan: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey firmly supports the
independence, territorial integrity and the legal government in
Azerbaijan, a Turkish high-ranking official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli made the
remarks at a weekly press conference in response to a Tuesday
speech by Azerbaijani President Geidar Aliyev, who said that there
had been sabotage force in his country whose objective was to
overthrow the legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli said, "We condemned the coup attempt in Azerbaijan (at
that time) and we are now condemning this attempt." He, however,
failed to touch the fact that some Turks were involved in the
sabotage activities in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the Turkish MPs, Aliyev, who arrived here on
Tuesday for a four-day official visit to Turkey, said that some
groups, including Turks in his country, had been attempting to
topple the present Azerbaijani government following the breakout
of the Nagorno-Karabakh armed conflict between Azerbaijan and
Armenia several years ago.
</P>
<P>
Aliyev had reportedly escaped an assassination attempt upon his
return to Baku, capital of Azerbaijan from a recent visit to Copenhagen,
Denmark.
</P>
<P>
So far, Azerbaijan and Armenia have made no progress in their
talks aimed at improving mutual relations due to their deepening
differences over a series of key issues, such as the future status
of the Nagorno-Karabakh, a disputed strip within the boundaries of
Azerbaijan but populated mostly by Armenians.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Aliyev's visit to Ankara was aimed at
further expanding political and economical cooperation between
Azerbaijan and Turkey, particularly in the field of oil and
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
In his speech delivered at the Turkish parliament, the
Azerbaijani leader stated that his country was giving priority for
transportation of Caspian oil and Turkmenistan gas to the
Baku-Ceyhan (southern Turkey) pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is an energy-starved country and has suffered an
economic loss of billions of U.S. dollars as a result of the
U.N. trade sanctions against Iraq. It has a urge to develop its
cooperation with its oil-rich neighboring countries in an effort
to solve its energy problem as well to increase its economic
strength. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
