<HEADLINE> Simitis: Greece Not to Negotiate Sovereign Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
today stressed that his country was in no way preparaed to
negotiate its sovereign rights in any form of dialogue and would
not accept any process which questioned the present status quo in
the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
"It is a fundamental position of the government that Greece does
not put up its sovereign rights, as these rights emanate
dialogue," Simitis said while addressing the ruling Panhellenic
Socialist Movement's parliamentary group.
</P>
<P>
On the Committees of Experts to be formed by Greece and Turkey,
he said that the purpose of the committee was to improve the
climate in bilateral relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, he emphasized that the committee in no way implied
commencement of a political dialogue nor any form of arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Greece had nothing to fear and nothing to lose, he said, adding
that the government policy aimed at improving ties with Turkey
through a step-by-step approach.
</P>
<P>
Greek-Turkish relations have been strained for decades over
territorial disputes and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, progress has been made by the two countries
to improve their bilateral ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
