<HEADLINE> World Bank Approves Big Loans for Two Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 7 (Xinhua) --The World Bank today announced the
approval of financing totaling 260 million U.S. dollars for
projects in India and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Indian State of Andhra Pradesh will launch a massive
cyclone recovery and mitigation program in response to the effects
of last year's disastrous cyclone and other natural disasters in
the state with 150 million dollars in assistance from the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The financing includes a 100 million equivalent credit through
the International Development Association (IDA), the World Bank's
concessionary lending wing for developing countries, and a loan of
50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project is aimed to assist the state government to
implement a hazard management system to prevent and mitigate the
damage caused by cyclones, floods and drought as well as to
rebuild public infrastructure and to enhance the government's
cyclone early warning capacity.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 220 million dollars. The
Indian government and the state government will contribute the
remaining cost.
</P>
<P>
Another loan of 110 million dollars will be provided for
Indonesia to help finance a Bali Urban Infrastructure Project. The
project will meet the basic needs in all urban centers and the
needs of growing urbanization in South Bali through urban
infrastructure investments, private sector participation, cultural
heritage conservation and institutional strengthening. With the
total cost of some 334.7 million dollars, the World Bank's loan is
some 32.9 percent of the total cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
