<HEADLINE> UNHCR Urges Inquiry on Treatment of Refugees in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) Sadako Ogata Wednesday welcomed a call by the
government of Rwanda for an independent international inquiry into
the way in which Rwandan refugees were being treated in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
A UNHCR official told reporters in New York the High
Commissioner, in a letter to the government of Rwanda, also said
the inquiry should also cover recent attacks on refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Ogata rejected as totally unacceptable Rwandan
government accusations that it was delaying the repatriation of
refugees in Zaire and was responsible for the deaths of 92
refugees on a train.
</P>
<P>
"The charges leveled by the Rwandan government and the Alliance
against the humanitarian relief effort in eastern Zaire are
outrageous, unfair and demonstrably false," Ogata said.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance, the anti-government force in Zaire, gave UNHCR a
60-day deadline beginning May 1 to complete the repatriation of
the Rwandan refugees following an international protest of the
violent dispersal of refugees in Kasese and Biaro and allegations
that many of them had been killed.
</P>
<P>
As of today, more than 12,000 of the 40,000 who have re-emerged
in Biaro have been airlifted to Rwanda since the operation started
on April 27.  
</P>
</TEXT>
