<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Foreign Exchange Inflow Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's gross international
reserves declined by 41.093 million U.S. Dollars between December
1996 and January this year from 220.655 million Dollars to
179.562 million Dollars as foreign exchanges inflows continued to
decline.
</P>
<P>
High government debt servicing and continued reluctance by
international donors to resume their assistance also led to the
decline, according to the Bank of Zambia (BOZ).
</P>
<P>
The reserves of 179.562 million Dollars can only meet Zambia's
imports for one month.
</P>
<P>
Under normal circumstances, international reserves are
supposed to meet the minimum of four months for a country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the BOZ also shows that between January and
March 1997, foreign exchange inflows amounted to only 34.989
million Dollars compared to 123.651 million Dollars received in
the last quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the low inflows in foreign exchanges, foreign
exchange outflow continued to increase as debt servicing consumed
more and more of its foreign exchanges.
</P>
<P>
During the period foreign exchange outflows from the BOZ
amounted to 85.564 million Dollars, of which 56.026 million
Dollars went to service government debts.
</P>
<P>
Because of the fall of foreign exchange inflows, the
government has resorted to domestic borrowing to meet external
debt servicing, but this has spelt doom for the country by way of
transferring resources from the productive sector to
non-productive areas.
</P>
<P>
The domestic debt by the end of last year was over 300 billion
Kwacha (about 231 million Dollars) while debt servicing in 1996
was 122 billion Kwacha (about 94 million Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
