<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Find HIV Infection Blockage in Lab Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 7 (Xinhua) -- A monoclonal antibody to CCR5, a
chemokine receptor on T cells, blocked HIV infection of those
cells in laboratory tests, it was reported in the May 5 issue of
the Journal of Experimental Medicine.
</P>
<P>
CCR5 is one of several co-receptors used by HIV to gain entry
to T cells. The results demonstrate that an anti-CCR5 agent can
block access to T cells by the strain of HIV found early in the
disease, the study's authors concluded.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at LeukoSite, Inc. of Cambridge, Massachusetts, the
Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center of New York and Dana-Farber
Cancer Institute of Boston collaborated on the study, according to
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
Recently, two chemokine receptors (CCR5 and CXCR4) were
identified as co-receptors through which HIV gains entry to T
cells. CCR5 is the portal for the macrophage-tropic HIV-1
strains, which predominate early in HIV infection, while CXCR4
allows the later-stage T-tropic HIV-1 strains to enter T cells.
Since the discovery of their role in HIV infection, the chemokine
co-receptors, especially CCR5, have become targets for the
development of new anti-AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
In November, LeukoSite announced it was collaborating with
Warner-Lambert on the discovery of small molecules that block the
CCR5 receptor, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
