<HEADLINE> Public Hearing on Africa's Forests Ends in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The two-day public hearing of
Africa's forests has ended here, concluding that the forests
should be given back to the indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the hearing organized by the World
Commission on Forests and Sustainable Development (WCFSD) on
Tuesday, Ola Ullsten, co-chairperson of the WCFSD, called on the
countries with the tropical forests to ensure that the
international community get the wood from them at right prices.
</P>
<P>
The public hearing is the fourth in a series organized by the
WCFSD to develop a better understanding of how forests could be
sustainably and more equitably managed.
</P>
<P>
Close to 100 eminent personalities from across the world
attending the meeting also came to the conclusion that the local
communities and governments have not received the right amount
for the wood taking out the forests.
</P>
<P>
In other word, the prices on the wood were too low compared to
what the exploiters and industrialists received after processing
the wood.
</P>
<P>
The next public hearing will be held in Russia after which the
commission will publish its final report in September this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
