<HEADLINE> Bosnian-Serb Found Guilty of War Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations International
War Crime Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia on Wednesday has
found a Bosnian-Serb guilty of crimes against humanity, according
to local television reports.
</P>
<P>
Reports said it was the first full international war crimes
trial since the end of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
Defendant Dusan Tadic, a former 41-year old cafe-owner, was
found guilty of 11 of 31 charges relating to the persecution and
torture of Bosnian Moslem civilians, many detained in camps in
north-west Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Tadic, who denied all the accusations, was accused to have
carried out numerous beatings of people in prison there, one of
whom later died from the injuries.
</P>
<P>
But he was acquited of nine murder charges, the judges
deciding by majority that there was a clear lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Tadic would remain in custody until
sentencing on 1 July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
