<HEADLINE> Bill on Road Safety to Be Tabled to Greek Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government would soon
submit a bill to the Parliament for discussion in order to combat
the increasing road accidents in the country.
</P>
<P>
Greek Transport and Communications Minister Haris Kastanidis
said today that the bill, currently being prepared by several
ministries, provided for the formation of a National Council for
Road Safety.
</P>
<P>
The proposed council would operate on a permanent basis and be
financially and administratively independent.
</P>
<P>
Each year, 2,000 people are killed and 32,000 injured in about
22,000 road accidents in Greece.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the accidents cost the Greek economy 150
billion drachmas (about 4.05 billion U.S. dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
Road accidents in Greece had reportedly increased by 105
percent over the past 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
