<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gold Market Much More Variation in 1996: GFMS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 7 (Xinhua) -- The gold market showed much more
variation during the course of 1996 relative to the preceding two
years due to the weakness of investment and increased supply, Gold
Fields Mineral Services (GFMS) said.
</P>
<P>
In its annual publication, Gold 1997, GFMS said that mine
production increased by 77 tons (3.4%) to 2,346 tons in 1996
after having declined marginally in each of the previous two
years.
</P>
<P>
Total supply amounted to 3,490 tons compared with 3,629
tons in 1995, with non-official sector sales rising to 239
tons from 182 tons and scrap increasing to 644 tons from 625
tons.
</P>
<P>
On demand side, jewellery fabrication rose for the third
successive year, showing an increase of 40 tons (1.4%) to a new
record level of 2,807 tons.
</P>
<P>
The use of gold in electronics, the second largest sector after
jewellery, rose for the fourth year in succession, with the
relatively modest increase of 1%.
</P>
<P>
The average prices in 1996, based on the average London (PM
fix), was 387.87 US dollars per ounce, 1 percent higher than 1995,
with GFMS noting that with the sustained rise in the dollar last
year, the gold price in other currencies showed substantial
year-on-year increases.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the developments in early 1997 and the outlook
for the remainder of the year, GFMS chief executive Stuart Murray
said at the launch of Gold 1997: "the price weakness since the
last quarter of 1996 has been to a large extent the result of poor
sentiment, stemming above all from fears about the future impact
of the official sector on the gold market."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the evidence uncovered by GFMS was that
official sector in the gold market was not a "one-way street".
</P>
<P>
"Even more importantly, the physical market, which tended to
hold back in the final months of the year as the price was
falling, has now kicked in with a vengeance and is once again
providing a rather solid floor at the 340 US dollars level in
spite of the continued strength of the dollar," Murray added.
</P>
<P>
On the question of the physical market gap, Murray noted that
"as in previous years, the current level of mine production and
scrap will continue to be insufficient to meet the demands for
fabrication and bar hoarding, and, the question is how this is
most likely to be filled in 1997." 
</P>
</TEXT>
